# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-the-great
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The **Palermo Stone** is one of seven surviving fragments of a stele known as the Royal Annals of the Old Kingdom of Ancient Egypt.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The stele contained a list of the kings of Egypt from the First Dynasty (c.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] 3150–2890 BCE) through to the early part of the Fifth Dynasty (c.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] 2498–2345 BCE) and noted significant events in each year of their reigns.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] It was probably made during the Fifth Dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The Palermo Stone is held in the Regional Archeological Museum Antonio Salinas in the city of Palermo, Italy, from which it derives its name.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The Palermo Stone and other fragments of the Royal Annals preserve what is probably the oldest historical text that has survived from Ancient Egypt and form a key source for Egyptian history in the Old Kingdom.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The Royal Annals stele, of which the Palermo Stone formed part, may originally have been about 60 cm high and 2.1m wide.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The fragments are composed of a compact hard black stone, probably a form of basalt.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The Palermo Stone itself is an irregular shield-shaped fragment, 43.5 cm high, 25 cm wide and 6.5 cm thick (maximum dimensions).
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The inscription on the "front" (recto) of the Palermo Stone consists of six horizontal bands or registers of hieroglyphic text running right to left.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The first register lists the names of predynastic kings of Lower Egypt (identified as such by the wearing of the Red Crown).
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The second and subsequent registers contain portions of royal annals for pharaohs of the First to Fourth Dynasties, that is lists of the key events in each year of the reign of each king, arranged chronologically.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The second register on the Palermo Stone begins with the final year entries for a king of the First Dynasty whose name is not preserved, but who is generally assumed to be either Narmer or Aha.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The rest of the second register is taken up with the first nine annual entries for this king's successor, who is again not named on the fragment, but is assumed to be either Aha or his successor Djer.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The remainder of the inscription on this side continues with royal annals down to the kings of the Fourth Dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The text continues on the "back" (verso) of the Palermo Stone, cataloguing events during the reigns of pharaohs down to Neferirkare Kakai, third ruler of the Fifth Dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] From the surviving fragments, it is unclear whether the Royal Annals originally continued beyond this point in time.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] Where a king is named, the name of his mother is also recorded, such as Betrest mother of the First Dynasty king Semerkhet and Meresankh I mother of the Fourth Dynasty king Seneferu.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] Information recorded in the Royal Annals (as preserved on the Palermo Stone) includes measurements of the height of the annual Nile flood (see Nilometer), the inundation, details of festivals (such as Sed festivals), taxation, sculpture, buildings, and warfare.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The original location of the stele is unknown and none of the surviving fragments have a secure archeological provenance.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] One fragment now in Cairo is said to have been found at an archaeological site at Memphis, while three other fragments now in Cairo were said to have been found in Middle Egypt.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] No find site for the Palermo Stone itself has been suggested.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The Palermo Stone was purchased by a Sicilian lawyer, Ferdinand Guidano, in 1859 and it has been in Palermo since 1866.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] On 19 October 1877, it was presented to the Palermo Archaeological Museum by the Guidano family, where it has remained since.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] There are five fragments of the Royal Annals in the Egyptian Museum in Cairo, four of which were acquired between 1895 and 1914.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The fifth was purchased on the antiquities market in 1963.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] One small fragment is in the Petrie Museum of University College London, forming part of the collection of the archeologist Sir Flinders Petrie (and purchased by him in 1914).
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The importance of the Palermo Stone was not recognized until it was noticed by a visiting French archaeologist in 1895.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The first full publication and translation was that done in 1902 by Heinrich Schäfer.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] There are uncertainties regarding the date of the Palermo Stone and of the Royal Annals it records.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] It is unknown whether the inscription was done all at once or whether it was added to over time.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] It is also unknown whether or not it dates from the latest period it describes (i.e. from no later than the Fifth Dynasty).
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] It has been suggested that the stele was made much later, perhaps in the Twenty-fifth Dynasty (747–656 BCE).
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] Even if the Royal Annals, as preserved by the Palermo Stone and other fragments, were not carved during, or soon after, the period they describe, they are directly based on an Old Kingdom original.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] It is also unknown whether all the surviving fragments are parts of the same stele or whether they come from separate copies.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] None of the smaller fragments held in Cairo have any clear provenance, and they may not all be genuine.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] Various parts of the ancient text are in widely varying states of preservation, which makes the text difficult to decipher.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] If the text is a later copy, rather than a Fifth Dynasty original, errors and invention may have crept in during the copying process.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] Names and positions of Pharaohs on Cairo Fragment 1 and the Palermo Stone from the front and back.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The Palermo Stone and the other associated fragments of the Royal Annals are vital sources for the history of the Old Kingdom, as they preserve names of members of the royal families during the first five dynasties, which are not otherwise recorded.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] In addition, while the names of Hor-Aha (1st dynasty), Anedjib (1st dynasty), Qa'a (1st dynasty), and Menkaure (4th dynasty) have not survived, their positions can still be inferred based on their surviving registers.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The New Kingdom Egyptian king lists, such as the Turin Canon (13th century BCE) and the Abydos king list (reign of Seti I, 1294–1279 BCE), identify Menes (probably Narmer) (c.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] 3100 or 3000 BCE) as the first king of the First Dynasty and so credit him with unifying Egypt.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] However, the top register of the *Royal Annals* names some predynastic rulers of Upper and Lower Egypt, presumably referring to a time before Egypt was unified.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] Identification of these kings with historical persons remains controversial.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] The Palermo stone also mentions at least fourteen predynastic pharaohs from Lower Egypt by their Horus name, of which at least five whose names have been fully destroyed.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh-of-lower-egypt] These may be mythical kings preserved through oral tradition, or may even be completely fictitious.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh] During the 2004 season of the North Kharga Oasis Survey (NKOS), a serekh was discovered on the north-eastern face of a sandstone massif under the direction of Dr.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh] It was isolated near the Darb Ain Amur, the ancient caravan route that connected the Kharga Oasis via the site of Umm el-Dabadib and Ain Amum to the Dakhla Oasis.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh] The serekh was located among other groups of graffiti with different styles and depths of cut, implying that they were from different time periods.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh] The serekh is surmounted by a falcon, as is conventional for serekhs, and contains a single sign.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh] The sign is an arm, or *A* (D36 in Gardiner's sign list).
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh] This name does not correspond to any other known Early Dynastic ruler.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh] One of the legs of the falcon reaches into the serekh, and the crouching position of the falcon is typical of serekhs from the Dynasty 0 or the First Dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh] Thus, it would seem that the serekh contains the Horus name 'A' of a previously unattested king belonging to Dynasty 0 or the First Dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/a-pharaoh] Surrounding the serekh on the sandstone massif are illustrations of various animals including a crocodile, a giraffe, a hippopotamus, an ostrich, a cow or bull, and a possibly pregnant oryx.
[src:alexander-the-great/abdalonymus] After Alexander the Great had subdued Sidon, he gave permission to Hephaestion to bestow its crown on whom he pleased.
[src:alexander-the-great/abdalonymus] Hephaestion offered it to two brothers with whom he lodged, but they declined it, alleging that according to their laws it could only be worn by one of royal blood.
[src:alexander-the-great/abdalonymus] Instead, they named Abdalonymus, who, notwithstanding his birth, had fallen into such poverty that he supported himself by the cultivation of a kitchen garden.
[src:alexander-the-great/abdalonymus] Hephaestion directed the brothers to carry the royal crown and robes to Abdalonymus.
[src:alexander-the-great/abdalonymus] They obeyed and found him weeding in his garden.
[src:alexander-the-great/abdalonymus] After causing him to wash, they invested him with the ensigns of royalty and conducted him to Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/abdalonymus] This prince, who discerned in him an aspect not unworthy of his origin, turning to those around him, said "I wish to know how he bore his poverty."—"Would to heaven," replied Abdalonymus, "I may as well bear my prosperity!
[src:alexander-the-great/abdalonymus] While Quintus Curtius confirms this story, as does Justin, Diodorus calls this person **Ballonimus**, and says he was made king of Tyre, not Sidon.
[src:alexander-the-great/abdalonymus] Plutarch removes the scene to Paphos, and names him **Alonymus**.
[src:alexander-the-great/abdalonymus] Curtius likely adorned the story with fictitious circumstances.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-eshuh] His exuberant titles included, "descendant of Sumu-la-El, princely heir of Samsu-iluna, eternal seed of kingship, mighty king, king of Babylon, king of the land of Sumer and Akkad, king who makes the four quarters be at peace." This was presumably achieved by his two aggressive military campaigns.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-eshuh] His fourth year-name records that he subdued the army of the Kassites.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-eshuh] The Chronicle of Early Kings recalls his damming of the Tigris River in a vain attempt to capture Ilum-ma-ilī, the founder of the Sealand Dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-eshuh] A clay cylinder fragment from Kish is tentatively assigned to this king because the events it commemorates coincide with three of his year-names.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-eshuh] It mentions the Tigris River (year “o” the damming of the Tigris), the Tigris gate (year “m” the *ká-gal-i*7*idigna*), the fashioning of a mace for Marduk (year “g”) and digging of the Zubi canal (year “I”).
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-eshuh] He is described as “the great champion” in his son, Ammī-ditāna's inscription, and in the genealogy of his descendant Ammī-ṣaduqa.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-eshuh] The Elamites under their king Kutir-nahhunte I raided into Babylon early in his reign and sacked 30 cities.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-eshuh] Two copies of a building inscription commemorate his construction activities at Luḫaia, a town founded by Hammurabi on the Araḫtum canal to the north of Babylon.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-eshuh] A single inscription exists found on an onyx eye stone dedicated to the goddess Ningal.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-eshuh] The *Uruk List of Kings and Sages* records that "during the reign of Abī-ešuḫ, the king, Gimil-Gula and Taqis-Gula were the scholars.".
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] It was the longest known dynasty of that state, which ruled throughout the period known as "Middle Babylonian" (1595-1000 BC).
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In the early portion of this the First Sealand dynasty ruled in the southern part of the region.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The Kassites (kaššû in Mesopotamian and possibly the Kossaioi of later Greek sources) were a people whose origins are unknown, although it has been suggested that they originated in the Zagros Mountains.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] It took their kings more than a century to consolidate their power in Babylon under conditions that remain unclear.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Despite their external origin, the Kassite kings did not change Babylon's ancestral traditions and, on the contrary, brought order to the country after the turbulence that marked the end of the first dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] They undertook a great deal of construction work, notably on the great temples, they contributed to the expansion of agricultural land, and under their auspices Babylonian culture flourished and expanded throughout the Ancient Near East.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The Kassite period is still very poorly known, due to the scarcity of sources relating to it, of which few are published.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The economic and social aspects, in particular, are very poorly documented, with the exception of what relates to the royal donations attested by the characteristic donation stelae of the period, the kudurrus.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Despite its long duration, the period of the dynasty is poorly documented: sources are scarce and few of them have been published.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Architectural and artistic traces of this period are also scanty; they come mainly from the site of Dur-Kurigalzu, where the only monumental complex of the Kassite period was found, consisting of a palace and several cult buildings.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Other buildings were discovered at several larger Babylonian sites, such as Nippur, Ur, and Uruk.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Other minor sites belonging to the Kassite kingdom have also been discovered in the Hamrin hills: Tell Mohammed, Tell Imlihiyeh and Tell Zubeidi.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Further afield, at the site of Terqa in the Middle Euphrates, and on the islands of Failaka (in what is now Kuwait) and Qal'at al-Bahrain in the Persian Gulf, there are also some traces of Kassite rule.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The low reliefs engraved on kudurrus and seal-cylinders are the best-known testimonies to the accomplishments of the artists of the time.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Brinkman, a leading expert on sources from the period, has estimated that approximately 12,000 texts from the period have been found, most of them belonging to the administrative archives from Nippur, of which only about 20% have been published.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] They were found in American excavations carried out mainly during the late 19th century and are stored in Istanbul and Philadelphia.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The rest come from other sites: there are forty tablets found at Dur-Kurigalzu that have been published, others from Ur, in the city of Babylon sets of private economic tablets and religious texts have been found that have not been published.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In the sites of the Hamrin hills, tablets have also been found, most of them unpublished, and there are also tablets whose provenance is unknown (the "*Peiser* archive").
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Most of this documentation is of an administrative and economic nature, but there are also some royal inscriptions and scholarly and religious texts.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The royal inscriptions of the Kassite kings, few in number and generally brief, provide little information about the political history of their dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] It is necessary to turn to the later sources, which are the historical chronicles written in the early first millennium BC, the Synchronic History and the P Chronicle, which provide information mainly about the conflicts between the Kassite kings and the Middle Assyrian Empire kings.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The royal inscriptions of the latter, which are very abundant, provide essential information about the same wars.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The Elamite royal inscriptions are somewhat less reliable.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] To these sources are also added some letters from the diplomatic correspondence of the Kassite kings with Egypt and the Hittites.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The former are part of the so-called Amarna Letters, found in Amarna, the ancient Akhetaten, capital of the pharaoh Akhenaten.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The latter were found at *Boğazköy*, on the site of the ancient Hittite capital, Hattusa.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The type of textual source concerning the administrative and economic life of Kassite Babylon that has attracted the most attention of scholars is a form of royal inscription, found on stelae known as kudurrus (which the Babylonians called *narû*), commemorating royal donations.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Some forty kudurrus are known from the Kassite period.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Their texts usually consist of a brief description of the donation and any privileges, a long list of witnesses, and curses for those who did not respect the act.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In 1595 BC, Samsi-Ditana, king of Babylon, was defeated by Mursili I, king of the Hittites, who seized the statue of Marduk kept in the Esagila, the great temple of the city of Babylon, which he took with him.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] This defeat marked the end of the Babylonian Amorite dynasty, already greatly weakened by the various rivals, among them the Kassites.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] According to the Babylonian royal list, Agum II would have taken over Babylon after the city was sacked by the Hittites.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] According to the same source, Agum II would have been the tenth sovereign of the dynasty of the Kassite kings (founded by a certain Gandas), who would have reigned who knows where during the second half of the 18th century BC.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Possibly the Kassites were allied with the Hittites and supported their campaign to seize power.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] There are no mentions of the exact origin of the kassites in ancient texts.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The first mention of them dates from the 18th century BC in Babylon, but they are also mentioned in Syria and Upper Mesopotamia in the following centuries.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] However, most experts place their origin in the Zagros mountain range, where Kassites were still found during the first half of the first millennium BC.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The first Kassite sovereign attested as king of Babylon seems to be Burna-Buriash I.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] This dynasty had as its rival that of the Sea Country, located south of Babylon around the cities of Uruk, Ur and Larsa, which was defeated in the early 15th century BC by the Kassite sovereigns Ulamburiash and Agum III.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The only notable territorial gain made by Kassite rulers thereafter was the island of Bahrain, then called Dilmum, where a seal bearing the name of a Babylonian governor of the island was discovered, although nothing is known about the duration of this rule.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The 14th and 13th centuries BC marked the heyday of Babylon's Kassite dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Its kings equaled their contemporary great sovereigns of Egypt, Hati, Mitanni and Assyria, with whom they maintained diplomatic relations, in which they have the privilege of bearing the title of "great king" (*šarru rabû*), which involved abundant correspondence and exchanges of gifts (*šulmānu*).
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] These exchanges were made as gifts of friendship or homage when a king was enthroned.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The diplomatic language was Babylonian Akkadian, in the so-called "Middle Babylonian" form, as was the case in the preceding period.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] 1359-1333 BC) married one of his daughters to the pharaoh Akhenaten (3rd quarter of the 14th century BC) and another to the Hittite king Suppiluliuma II, while he himself espoused the daughter of the Assyrian king Ashur-uballit I.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] There were also Babylonian princesses who married Elamite sovereigns.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] These practices were intended to strengthen the ties between the different royal houses, which in the last two cases were direct neighbors, in order to avoid political tensions.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] With more distant partners, such as the Hittites, they were essentially a form of prestige and influence, since the Babylonian princesses and the specialists (doctors and scribes) who were sent to the Hittite court were protagonists of Babylonian cultural influences in the Hittite kingdom.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Babylon became involved in a series of conflicts with Assyria when Assyrian ruler Ashur-uballit I broke free from Mitanni rule in 1365 BC, which marked the beginning of a multi-secular confrontation between northern and southern Mesopotamia.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] 1359-1333 BC) initially took a dim view of Assyrian independence, as he considered this region one of his vassals, but eventually married the daughter of the Assyrian king, with whom he had a son, Kara-hardash.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The latter ascended the throne in 1333 BC, but was assassinated shortly thereafter and was succeeded by Nazi-Bugash.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Ashur-uballit reacted to his grandson's murder and invaded Babylon to put his other grandson, Kurigalzu II (r.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The latter kept his allegiance to his grandfather until he died, but provoked the next Assyrian king Enlil-nirari, which led to a series of conflicts that lasted for over a century and culminated in the confrontation between Kashtiliash IV (r.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] 1232-1225 BC) of Babylon and Tukulti-Ninurta I (r. ca.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The latter invaded and devastated Babylon, sacking the capital, from where he deported thousands of people.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The situation then became increasingly confused, as the Assyrians failed to establish a lasting domination in Babylon, despite the will of Tukulti-Ninurta, who had his victory described in a long epic text (the Epic of Tukulti-Ninurta) and proclaimed himself king of Babylon.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The conflicts continued and escalated when the Elamite king Kidin-Hutran (r.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] 1245-1215 BC) became involved, possibly in solidarity with the Kassite kings, to whom he was linked by marriage.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Kidin-Hutran devastated Nippur and made the situation difficult for the Assyrian-imposed rulers in Babylon, who were deposed one after another until 1217 BC.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] After the assassination of Tukulti-Ninurta in 1208 BC and the internal turmoil that followed in Assyria, the kings of Babylon were able to regain their autonomy, to the extent that it was the Babylonian king Merodach-Baladan I (r.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] 1171-1159 BC) who helped the Assyrian king Ninurta-apil-Ecur take power in the northern kingdom, before the latter turned against him unsuccessfully.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Shortly after the end of these conflicts, the Elamite armies entered Mesopotamia, commanded by their king Shutruk-Nakhunte (r.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] 1185-1160 BC), at a time when Babylon and Assyria were weakened by recent warfare.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The Elamite king's intervention in Babylon may have been motivated by his desire to assert his rights to the Babylonian throne resulting from his family ties to the Kassite dynasty, at a time when succession disputes had weakened the legitimacy of the Babylonian sovereigns.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In 1160 BC, at a time when Merodach-Baladan had managed to stabilize power in Babylon, the Elamite monarch Shutruk-Nakhunte invaded Babylon and sacked its major cities.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] It was during this period that several major monuments of Mesopotamian history were taken to Susa, the Elamite capital.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Among the looted pieces were several statues and stelae, such as that of the victory of Naram-Sim of Akkad or the Code of Hammurabi, as well as other stelae from various eras, including kassite kudurrus.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] After several years of resistance led by Kassite sovereigns, the next Elamite king, Kutir-Nacunte III, dealt the coup de grace to the Kassite dynasty in 1155 BC and took the statue of the god Marduk to Elam as a symbol of Babylon's submission.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Documentation about the Kassite period is scant compared to the preceding period, focusing mainly on the 14th and 13th centuries BC.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] It has also been little studied, so little is known about the socioeconomic aspects of Babylon at that time.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The largest body of documentation is a batch of 12,000 tablets found at Nippur, of which only a small part has been published and studied.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] A few archives have also been found elsewhere, but in small quantity.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Added to these sources are the kudurrus (see below) and some royal inscriptions.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The Kassite king was designated by several titles.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In addition to the more traditional "king of the four regions" or "king of totality" (*šar kiššati*), the new title "king of Karduniash" (*šar māt karduniaš*) was used, or the original "*xacanacu* of Enlil" used by the two kings named Kurigalzu.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The first titles indicate that the king considered himself ruler of a territory that included the entire Babylonian region.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The Kassite kings took up all the traditional attributes of the Mesopotamian monarchies: warrior kings, supreme judges of the kingdom, and undertakers of works, notably the maintenance and restoration of the temples of the traditional Mesopotamian deities.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The entire royal family was involved in holding the high offices: there are examples of a king's brother commanding an army, or a king's son becoming the high priest of the god Enlil.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Notwithstanding their ethnic background, the Kassite influences on the political and religious usages of the court seem to have been limited.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The names of the sovereigns are Kassite at the beginning of the dynasty, referring to gods of this people, such as Burias, Harbe, or Marutas, but later mix Kassite and Akkadian terms.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The royal dynasty placed itself under the protection of a pair of Kassite deities, Sucamuna and Sumalia, who had a temple in the city of Babylon at which kings were crowned.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Although, according to a text of the time, the official capital was later moved to Dur-Kurigalzu, the kings continued to be honored in Babylon, which preserved its status as the main capital.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Dur-Kurigalzu was a new city founded by Kurigalzu II (r.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] 1332-1308 BC), where the Kassite kings were honored by the chiefs of the Kassite tribes.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Apparently, this secondary capital seems to be more closely linked to the dynasty, without really shadowing Babylon, whose prestige remained intact.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In the Kassite period some new titles appeared for dignitaries close to the king, such as *šakrumaš*, a term of Kassite origin that apparently designated a military chief, or the *kartappu*, who was originally a horse driver.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Although the organization of the Kassite army is very poorly known, it is known that this period saw important innovations in military techniques, with the appearance of the light car and the employment of horses, which was apparently one of the Kassite specialties.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Among the high dignitaries, the sukkallu (a vague term that can be translated as "minister") were still present.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The roles of all these characters are ill-defined and probably unstable.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The Kassite nobility is not well known, but it is generally admitted that they held the most important positions and had large estates.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] A little more is known about provincial administration.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The kingdom was divided into provinces (*pīhatu*), headed by governors, usually called *šakin māti* or *šaknu*, to which can be added the eventual tribal territories headed by a *bēl bīti*, an office we talk about below.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The governor of Nippur bore the particular title of *šandabakku* (in Sumerian: GÚ.EN.NA) and had more power than the rest.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] This office of governor of Nippur is only well known because of the abundance of archives found in that city about the Kassite period.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Governors often succeeded each other within the same family.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] At the local level, villages and towns were administered by a "mayor" (*hazannu*), whose functions had a judicial component, although there were judges (*dayyānu*).
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The subordinate administrative posts were held by Babylonians, who were well trained for such tasks.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The Kassites do not seem to have had much inclination for the profession of scribe-administrator.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] All subjects were obliged to pay taxes to the royal power, which in some cases could be paid with works: sometimes it happened that the administration requisitioned certain goods from private individuals.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] These tax contributions are known mainly because they are mentioned in the kudurrus, which record the exemption for certain lands.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In the Kassite period some innovations were made in the field of administrative organization, which are partly due to Kassite traditions.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Some territories were called "houses" (in Akkadian: *bītu*), headed by a chief (*bēl bīti*, "house chief"), who usually claimed to be descended from an eponymous common ancestor of the group.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] This was long interpreted as a kassite mode of tribal organization, with each tribe having a territory that it administered.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] This view has recently been challenged, and it has been proposed that these "houses" of family property inherited from an ancestor were a form of province that complemented the administrative grid described above, in which chiefs were appointed by the king.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The dominant economic institutions in Babylon continued to be the "great bodies," the palaces and temples.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] But except for the case of the lands of the governor of Nippur, there is little documentation about these institutions.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] One of the rare aspects of the economic organization of the Kassidic period on which there is much documentation is that of the land grants made by the kings: there are thousands of unpublished tablets waiting to be published so that knowledge about this period can be expanded.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] This is a particular phenomenon that seems to have been initiated in this period, because during the previous period land was granted in a non-definitive way.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] These donations are recorded in kudurrus, and 40 have been found from the Kassite dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] These are stelae divided into several sections: the description of the donation, with the rights and duties of the beneficiary (taxes, corvees, exemptions), the divine curses to which those who did not respect the donation were subjected, and often carved low reliefs.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The kudurrus were placed in temples, under divine protection.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Usually the donations involved very large properties, 80 to 1,000 hectares (250 ha on average) and the recipients were high dignitaries close to the king: high officials, members of the court, especially the royal family, generals or priests.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] They were a reward for people's loyalty or for acts for which they had distinguished themselves.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The great temples of Babylon also received important estates: Esagila, the temple of Marduk of Babylon, received 5,000 ha during the period.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The land was granted with agricultural workers, who became dependent on the temple.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Sometimes the grants were accompanied by tax exemptions or corvees.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In extreme cases, the beneficiaries had power over the local population, which took the place of the provincial administration, from which they were protected by special clauses.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The grants did not concern most of the land, which the sovereign could not alienate and which continued to be administered in the same ways as described above from previous periods.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Very little is known about the economy of Kassite Babylon.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The situation in the rural world is obscure as sources are very limited apart from what is known from kudurrus and some economic tables of the period from mainly Nippur.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Archaeological surveys carried out in various areas of the Lower Mesopotamian plain indicate that economic recovery was slow after the crisis at the end of the Paleobylonian period, during which the number of occupied areas declined sharply.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] This situation may have been accompanied by a decline in agricultural production, possibly aggravated in some regions (like Uruk, for example) by displacement of water courses.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The land grants made by the kings seem to have focused mainly on lands located in the vicinity of cultivated areas, which may reflect a desire to take back areas that had become uncultivated after the end of the previous period.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] It is also noted that the royal administration engaged in the exploitation of intensively cultivated areas around Nippur.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] However, little is even known about irrigated crops, the main economic sector of Babylon.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Very little is also known about local crafts and trade.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In the archives of Dur-Kurigalzu there is a record of deliveries of raw materials such as metal and stone to craftsmen working for a temple, a common situation in the organization of crafts in ancient Mesopotamia.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Apparently, long-distance trade was quite developed, particularly with the Persian Gulf (Dilmun, in present-day Bahrain) and with the Mediterranean Levant.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The Amarna Letters show that the king was interested in the fates of the Babylonian merchants as far as Palestine, but he cannot state whether this is an indication that these merchants (always called *tamkāru*) worked for the royal palace partially or completely.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The exchanges of goods carried out in the framework of diplomacy between the royal courts, although they cannot be identified as trade proper, did contribute to the circulation of goods on an international scale for the elites.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Thus, the cordial diplomatic relations maintained by the Kassites with Egypt seem to have provided an important influx of gold to Babylon, which would have allowed prices to be based on the gold standard rather than silver for the first time in Mesopotamian history.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The Mesopotamian pantheon of the Kassite period did not undergo profound changes from the preceding period.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] This can be seen in the low relief of a kudurru from Meli-Shipak II (1186-1172 B.C.) currently preserved in the Louvre Museum.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The deities invoked as guarantors of the land grant that is consecrated on this stele are represented according to a functional and hierarchical organization.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] On the upper part are symbols of the deities that traditionally dominated the Mesopotamian pantheon: Enlil, who remained the king of the gods, Anu, Sin, Shamash, Ishtar and Enki.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] His son Nabu, god of wisdom, and Gula, goddess of medicine, also enjoyed great popularity.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The original Kassite deities did not acquire an important place in the Babylonian pantheon.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The main ones are known through a few mentions in the texts: the patron couple of the Sucamuna-Sumalia dynasty already mentioned, the storm god Burias, the warrior god Marutas, the sun god Surias, and Harbe, who seems to have had a sovereign function.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The various works sponsored in the temples by the Kassite monarchs are poorly known at the architectural level, but there are indications that some innovations were made.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] A small temple with original decoration built inside Eanna, the main religious complex of Uruk, is known to have been constructed during the reign of Caraindas (15th century BC), and of works carried out at Ebabar, the temple of the god Shamash in Larsa, during the reign of Burna-Buriash II (ca.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Besides these works, Kurigalzu sponsored the worship of the deities worshipped in these different temples.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The school texts from the Kassite period found at Nippur show that the learning structures of the scribes and the literates remained similar to those of the Paleobylonian period.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] However, a major change took place: texts in Akkadian were included in the school curricula, which kept pace with the evolution of Mesopotamian literature, which increasingly became written in that language, although Sumerian continued to be used.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The Kasside period also saw the development of "Standard Babylonian," a literary form of Akkadian that remained fixed in the following centuries in literary works and can therefore be considered a "classic" form of the language.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] From then on, new Mesopotamian literary works were written exclusively in this dialect.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] During the Kassite period, several fundamental works of Mesopotamian literature were written and there was mainly the canonization and standardization of works from previous periods that until then had circulated under various variants.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Akkadian versions of some Sumerian myths were also prepared.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The Kassite period seems to have enjoyed prestige among the literates of the following periods, who sometimes looked for an ancestor among the literates who were supposed to have been active during this period.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Important achievements of this period include the writing of canonical versions of numerous lexical lists, the writing of a "Hymn to Shamash," one of the most notable in ancient Mesopotamia, as well as another dedicated to Gluttony.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The standard version of the "Epic of Gilgamesh," which according to tradition is by the exorcist Sîn-lēqi-unninni, is often attributed to this same period.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] However, precise dating of the literary works is often impossible: at best, these achievements can be placed in the period between 1400 and 1000 BC.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] One of the most remarkable aspects of the literature of the Middle Babylonian period is the fact that several works reflect a deepening of reflections on human destiny, in particular the relations between gods and men.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] This is found in several major works of Mesopotamian sapiential literature, a genre that had existed for a millennium, but which then reached its full maturity and proposed deeper reflections.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The Dialogue of Pessimism, written after the Kassite period, proposes a similar reflection in the form of a satirical dialogue.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The changes leading to the standard version of the Epic of Gilgamesh would also reflect these developments: whereas the previous version accentuated mainly the heroic aspect of Gilgamexe, the new version seems to introduce a reflection on human destiny, in particular on the inevitability of death.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] As with other cultural aspects, the arrival of the Kassites did not change Babylonian architectural and artistic traditions, although some developments did occur.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] A few housing blocks from this period have been uncovered in the Babylonian sites at Ur, Nippur, and Dur-Kurigalzu, where no major changes from the preceding period have been noted.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In contrast, the religious architecture, although poorly known, seems to witness some innovations.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The small shrine built under the Caraindas of the Eanna complex at Uruk has a facade decorated with molded baked bricks representing deities protecting the waters, a type of ornamentation that is an innovation of the Kassite period.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] However, official architecture is mainly represented in Dur-Kurigalzu, a new city ordered built by one of the kings named Kurigalzu, where the large size of the main buildings shows that a new phase of monumentality has been entered.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In that city, a part of a vast palace complex 420,000 m2 (4,500,000 sq ft) in area, organized around eight units, was uncovered.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Each of the sections of this building may have been assigned to the main Kassite tribes.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] According to a text of the time, the palace of Dur-Kurigalzu was the place where these tribes formally recognized the power of the new kings when they ascended the throne, which happened after the coronation had taken place in the city of Babylon, which remained the main capital.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Some of the rooms were decorated with paintings, fragments of which have been found, including scenes of processions of male characters, who are identified as dignitaries of the Kassite tribes.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Southeast of the palace was a religious complex dedicated to Enlil, dominated by a ziggurat whose ruins still stand over 57 meters high.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Other temples were also built on this site.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The stone sculpture of the Kassite period is represented mainly by the low reliefs decorating the kudurrus already mentioned several times, whose iconography is particularly interesting.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In them are symbols of the deities that guarantee the legal acts recorded on the stela, which are considerably developed by the artists of this period and replace the anthropomorphic representations of the deities, which allowed many deities to be represented in a minimum space.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Nevertheless, sculptors continue to make figurative representations of characters on these stelae, as was common in previous periods.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] A kudurru from Meli-Shipak represents this king holding hands with his daughter, to whom he made the donation of property recorded in the stela text, and presenting her to the goddess Nanaia, guarantor of the act, who is seated on a throne.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Above are depicted the symbols of the astral deities Sin (Crescent Moon), Shamash (solar disk) and Ishtar (morning star, Venus).
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The first forms of glass also appeared in this period, and are represented in the artistic field by vases decorated with mosaics.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The glyptic themes experienced various evolutions during the second half of the second millennium BC, which experts divide into three or four types but whose chronology and geographical distribution are still poorly determined.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The type of seal that predominated at the beginning took up the tradition of the preceding period; it associates a seated and a praying deity, with the text accompanying the image, very developed, consisting of a votive prayer; the engraved material is generally a hard stone.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The next type of the kassite period is more original; a central character is depicted, often a kind of kthonic figure, a god on a mountain or emerging from the waters, or a hero, a demon, or trees surrounded by genies.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The third kassite type is characterized by Assyrian influences and the presence of real or hybrid animals.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The later style (also called "pseudo-Kassite"), developed at the end of the Kassite period or shortly thereafter, was engraved on soft stones and the images were dominated by animals associated with trees and framed with friezes of triangles.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In all probability the dynasty ruled Babylon for around 350 years.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The era of the early Kassite rulers is characterized by a dearth of surviving historical records.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The principal sources of evidence for the existence of these monarchs are the Babylonian *King List A* (BM 33332) which shows just the first six, and the Assyrian *Synchronistic King List* (A.117, Assur 14616c). which gives their names indistinctly, and are compared below, after Brinkman.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The tenth position of the Synchronistic King List is occupied by Burna-Buriyåš I.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] A first-millennium BC school text (BM 77438) purporting to be a copy of one of his inscriptions credits Gandaš with the conquest of *Bà-bà-lam*.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Agum I may be the subject of a 7th-century BC historical inscription (K.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] 3992) which also mentions Damiq-ilῑšu, the last king of the 1st Dynasty of Isin.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] 4149+) names Agum ra-bi-i (*rabû* = "the great"), Kaštiliašu, Abi-Rattaš, and Ur-šigurumaš as ancestors of Agum-Kakrime (Agum II), each son of the preceding except Ur-šigurumaš, who is described as descendant of Abi-Rattaš.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The traces in the ninth position of the *Synchronistic King List* do not allow for the name *Agum*, so *Kakrime* has been suggested as an alternative.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Excavations in the southeastern suburb of Baghdad known as Tell Muhammad yielded two archives of the first Sealand Dynasty period.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Those from level 3, excavated in the 1990s, were dated with year names, for example: "Year water carried King Ḫurduzum up to the city".
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Those from level 2, excavated in the 1970s, possessed a slightly different date formula, for example: "Year 38 Babylon was resettled (MU.38.KAM.MA *ša* KA2.DINGIR.RAki *uš.bu*) Year King Šipta'ulzi", and are mostly silver and cereal loans.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The layers are thought to be around a generation apart.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The resettlement of Babylon has been linked to the aftermath of the Hittite sack of the city under Mursili I.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] It has been proposed that the two kings be identified with those in positions seven and eight, and that a slightly different reading of Ḫurbazum for Ḫurduzum be adopted, thought this has been disputed.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Possibly the earliest military action involving the Kassites is preserved in the date formula (as Ka-aš-šu-ú) for Samsu-iluna's ninth year (c.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The year name reads "Year in which Samsu-iluna the king (defeated) the totality of the strength of the army / the troops of the Kassites".
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] A year name, possibly the 4th, of Abi-Ešuh (c.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] 1707 BC) the son and successor of Samsu-iluna reads "Year Abi-Ešuh the king by the exalted command of An, Enlil and the great power of Marduk (subdued) the armies and troops of the Kassites".
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Around the same time a king of the middle Euphrates kingdom called Ḫana, successor state of Mari, bore the name Kaštiliašu, but apart from this name there is no evidence that the region was occupied by Kassites during this time, and he was succeeded by Šunuhru-Ammu, whose name is Amorite.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Two seal impressions (TQ5-T105 and TQ5-T99) found at Ḫana's capital Terqa read, "[Gi]mil Ninkar[ak], son of Arši-a[ḫum], [se]rvant of Ila[ba], [and K]aštili[ašu]".
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Frayne speculates that Kaštiliašu may have been a Babylonian installed by Samsu-iluna after his defeat of Iadiḫ-abu and not a native ruler.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Another possible early Kassite ruler, Hašmar-galšu, is known from five inscriptions from the Nippur area.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Three of the inscriptions (NBC 6103, MMA 41.160.187, and Otago Museum E47.308) on diorite stone blocks, 13 by 7 centimeter slabs, are duplicates (one has minor sign differences) with a 5 line Sumerian inscription reading "A gift of Hašmargalšu.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] A stone slab of the Ekur for Enlil, his king.".
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] His name is prefaced by a dingir ie "dHa-aš-mar-gal-šu" though he is not designated as a king.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In another 8 line votive clay cone inscription (YBC 2353) he reports building a temple for "dimin-bi" (‘The Seven Gods’ ie.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Sebitti) and calls himself the son of "Ma-la-ab-Har-be" (Malab-Harbe).
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The last is a 15 line brown stone brick inscription (A 7570) dedicating a brick in the Great Gate of the Ekur temple and he again called himself the son of Malab-Ḫarbe.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] In the later two texts he is described as nita kala-ga ("mighty man") a term usually reserved for rulers.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] The consensus is that Hašmar-galšu is probably but not with certainty a Kassite ruler of an unknown date.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Unfortunately, due to the shortage of historical sources from the Kassite period much of the detail in the following comes from much later Neo-Assyrian/Neo-Babylonian king lists, chronicles, and omens, each with their own issues and agendas and is suspect.
[src:alexander-the-great/abi-rattash] Note that the relative order of Kadashman-Turgu and Kadashman-Enlil II have been questioned.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] The **Abydos Dynasty** is hypothesized to have been a short-lived local dynasty ruling over parts of Middle and Upper Egypt during the Second Intermediate Period in Ancient Egypt.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] The Abydos Dynasty would have been contemporaneous with the Fifteenth and Sixteenth Dynasties, from approximately 1650 to 1600 BC.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] It would have been based in or around Abydos and its royal necropolis might have been located at the foot of the *Mountain of Anubis*, a hill resembling a pyramid in the Abydene desert, close to a rock-cut tomb built for pharaoh Senusret III.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] The existence of an Abydos Dynasty was first proposed by Detlef Franke and later elaborated on by Kim Ryholt in 1997.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] Ryholt observes that two attested kings of this period, Wepwawetemsaf (*Wepwawet is his protection*) and Pantjeny (*He of Thinis*), bore names in connection with Abydos: Wepwawet being an important Abydene god and Thinis being a prominent city, located a few miles north of Abydos.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] Additionally, Wepwawetemsaf, Pantjeny and Snaaib, another king of the period, are each known from single stelae discovered in Abydos, which could be a sign that this was their seat of power.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] Finally, Ryholt argues that the existence of an Abydos Dynasty would explain 16 entries of the Turin canon at the end of the 16th Dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] The Abydos Dynasty may have come into existence in the time lapse between the fall of the 13th Dynasty with the conquest of Memphis by the Hyksos and the southward progression of the Hyksos to Thebes.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] The existence of the dynasty may have been vindicated in January 2014, when the tomb (CS9) of the previously unknown pharaoh Senebkay was discovered in the southern part of Abydos, an area called "Anubis Mountain" in ancient times.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] If Senebkay indeed belongs to the Abydos Dynasty, his tomb might signal the royal necropolis of this dynasty, adjacent to the tombs of the Middle Kingdom rulers.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] In 2025, the discovery of another royal tomb at the "Anubis Mountain" was announced; this tomb was a little older than Senebkay's but much larger.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] However, the occupant's name had not yet been found in the heavily damaged structure, possibly due to the action of tomb robbers.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] The excavators linked the tomb to the early Abydos Dynasty, and believe that the tomb belongs to a predecessor to Senebkay because the tomb was built in a section of the necropolis that the researchers believe was established earlier in time.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] The existence of an Abydos Dynasty is not agreed by all scholars.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] For example, Marcel Marėe observes that a workshop operating from Abydos and producing stelae for two kings associated with the Abydos Dynasty, Pantjeny and Wepwawetemsaf, also likely produced the stela of Rahotep of the 17th Dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] Thus if the Abydos Dynasty did exist, this workshop would have been producing stelae for two enemy dynasties, something which he judges to be rather unlikely.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] It remains unclear, however, whether these two dynasties coexisted at any one time: for instance, in Ryholt's reconstruction of the Second Intermediate Period, they are separated by c.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] Countering the argument in favor of the Abydos Dynasty based on the tomb of Senebkay, Alexander Ilin-Tomich argues that certain Middle Kingdom pharaohs, such as Senusret III and Sobekhotep IV, also have their tombs at Abydos, yet nobody places these kings into an Abydos-based dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] Instead, he wonders whether Senebkay might be a king of the Theban 16th Dynasty.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] If the Abydos Dynasty was indeed a dynasty, the seat of its power would probably have been either Abydos or Thinis.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] A possible graffito of Wepwawetemsaf was discovered by Karl Richard Lepsius in the tomb BH2 of the 12th Dynasty nomarch Amenemhat at Beni Hasan, about 250 km North of Abydos, in Middle Egypt.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] If the attribution of this graffito is correct and if Wepwawetemsaf did belong to the Abydos Dynasty, then its territory might have extended that far north.
[src:alexander-the-great/abydos-dynasty] Since the dynasty was contemporaneous with the 16th Dynasty, the territory under Abydene control could not have extended farther than Hu, 50 km south of Abydos.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Born in Pella, Macedon, Alexander was tutored by philosopher and polymath Aristotle until the age of 16.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In 335 BC, shortly after assuming the throne of Macedon, he launched a campaign in the Balkans and reasserted control over Thrace and parts of Illyria before marching on the city of Thebes, which was subsequently destroyed.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then assumed leadership of the League of Corinth, created by his father.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] With this authority over all Greeks he launched a pan-Hellenic invasion of the Persian Achaemenid Empire in 334 BC, and with it began a series of campaigns which lasted for ten years.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Following his conquest of Asia Minor and a series of decisive battles, particularly at Issus and Gaugamela, the power of the Achaemenid Empire was broken.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He subsequently overthrew Darius III and conquered the Achaemenid Empire in its entirety.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] After the fall of Persia, the Macedonian Empire held a vast swath of territory between the Adriatic Sea and the Indus River.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander endeavored to reach the "ends of the world and the Great Outer Sea" and invaded India in 326 BC, achieving an important victory over Porus, an ancient Indian king of present-day Punjab, at the Battle of the Hydaspes.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Facing mutiny from troops, he was eventually forced to turn back at the Beas River, and later died in 323 BC in Babylon, Mesopotamia, the city which he had planned to make the capital of his empire, while on his return to Greece.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's death put an end to his planned invasion of Arabia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In the years following his death, a series of civil wars broke out across the Macedonian Empire, eventually leading to its disintegration at the hands of the Diadochi.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's death marks the conventional beginning of the Hellenistic period.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Through his conquests, he built a legacy that includes the cultural diffusion and syncretism, which gave rise to Greco-Buddhism and Hellenistic Judaism.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He founded more than twenty cities, with the most prominent being the city of Alexandria in Egypt.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's establishment of Greek colonies and the spreading of Greek culture led to Hellenistic civilization becoming a major force in the ancient world, influencing regions as far east as the Indian subcontinent.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The Hellenistic period developed through the Roman Empire into modern Western culture; the Greek language became the *lingua franca* of the region and was the predominant language of the Byzantine Empire until its collapse in 1453 AD.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander became a legendary hero similar to Achilles, featuring prominently in the historical and mythical traditions of both Greek and non-Greek cultures.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] His military achievements and successes in battle made him the touchstone against which many later military leaders would judge themselves.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] His tactics remain a significant subject of study in military academies worldwide.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Legends of Alexander's exploits were coalesced into the 3rd century *Alexander Romance* which, in the premodern period, went through over one hundred recensions, translations, and derivations and was translated into almost every European vernacular and every language of the Islamic world.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] After the Bible, it was the most popular form of European literature.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander III was born in Pella, the capital of the Kingdom of Macedon, on the sixth day of the ancient Greek month of Hekatombaion, which probably corresponds to 20 July 356 BC (although the exact date is uncertain).
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He was the son of the king of Macedon, Philip II of the Argead dynasty and his fourth wife, Olympias (daughter of Neoptolemus I, Aeacid king of Epirus).
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Although Philip had seven or eight wives, Olympias was his principal wife for some time, likely because she gave birth to Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Several legends surround Alexander's birth and childhood.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the ancient Greek biographer Plutarch, on the eve of the consummation of her marriage to Philip, Olympias dreamed that her womb was struck by a thunderbolt that caused a flame to spread "far and wide" before dying away.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Sometime after the wedding, Philip is said to have seen himself, in a dream, securing his wife's womb with a seal engraved with a lion's image.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch offered a variety of interpretations for these dreams: that Olympias was pregnant before her marriage, indicated by the sealing of her womb; or that Alexander's father was Zeus.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Ancient commentators were divided about whether the ambitious Olympias promulgated the story of Alexander's divine parentage, variously claiming that she had told Alexander, or that she dismissed the suggestion as impious.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] On the day Alexander was born, Philip was preparing a siege on the city of Potidea on the peninsula of Chalcidice.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] That same day, Philip received news that his general Parmenion had defeated the combined Illyrian and Paeonian armies and that his horses had won at the Olympic Games.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] It was also said that on this day, the Temple of Artemis in Ephesus, one of the Seven Wonders of the World, burnt down.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] This led Hegesias of Magnesia to say that it had burnt down because Artemis was away, attending the birth of Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Such legends may have emerged when Alexander was king, and possibly at his instigation, to show that he was superhuman and destined for greatness from conception.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In his early years, Alexander was raised by a nurse, Lanike, sister of Alexander's future general Cleitus the Black.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Later in his childhood, Alexander was tutored by the strict Leonidas, a relative of his mother, and by Lysimachus of Acarnania.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was raised in the manner of noble Macedonian youths, learning to read, play the lyre, ride, fight, and hunt.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander was ten years old, a trader from Thessaly brought Philip a horse, which he offered to sell for thirteen talents.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The horse refused to be mounted, and Philip ordered it away.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander, however, detecting the horse's fear of its own shadow, asked to tame the horse, which he eventually managed.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch stated that Philip, overjoyed at this display of courage and ambition, kissed his son tearfully, declaring: "My boy, you must find a kingdom big enough for your ambitions.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Macedon is too small for you", and bought the horse for him.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander named it Bucephalas, meaning "ox-head".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Bucephalas carried Alexander as far as modern day India.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] When Bucephalas died (because of old age, according to Plutarch, at age 30), Alexander named a city after him, Bucephala.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander was 13, Philip began to search for a tutor, and considered such academics as Isocrates and Speusippus, the latter offering to resign from his stewardship of the Academy to take up the post.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In the end, Philip chose Aristotle and provided the Temple of the Nymphs at Mieza as a classroom.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In return for teaching Alexander, Philip agreed to rebuild Aristotle's hometown of Stageira, which Philip had razed, and to repopulate it by buying and freeing the ex-citizens who were slaves, or pardoning those who were in exile.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Mieza was like a boarding school for Alexander and the children of Macedonian nobles, such as Ptolemy, Hephaestion, and Cassander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Many of these students would become his friends and future generals, and are often known as the "Companions".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Aristotle taught Alexander and his companions about medicine, philosophy, morals, religion, logic, and art.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Under Aristotle's tutelage, Alexander developed a passion for the works of Homer, and in particular the *Iliad*; Aristotle gave him an annotated copy, which Alexander later carried on his campaigns.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was able to quote Euripides from memory.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In his youth, Alexander was also acquainted with Persian exiles at the Macedonian court, who received the protection of Philip II for several years as they opposed Artaxerxes III.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Among them were Artabazos II and his daughter Barsine, possible future mistress of Alexander, who resided at the Macedonian court from 352 to 342 BC, as well as Amminapes, future satrap of Alexander, and a Persian nobleman named Sisines.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] This gave the Macedonian court a good knowledge of Persian issues, and may even have influenced some of the innovations in the management of the Macedonian state.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Suda writes that Anaximenes of Lampsacus was one of Alexander's teachers, and that Anaximenes also accompanied Alexander on his campaigns.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] At the age of 16, Alexander's education under Aristotle ended.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip II had waged war against the Thracians to the north, which left Alexander in charge as regent and heir apparent.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] During Philip's absence, the Thracian tribe of Maedi revolted against Macedonia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander responded quickly and drove them from their territory.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The territory was colonized, and a city, named Alexandropolis, was founded.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Upon Philip's return, Alexander was dispatched with a small force to subdue the revolts in southern Thrace.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Campaigning against the Greek city of Perinthus, Alexander reportedly saved his father's life.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Meanwhile, the city of Amphissa began to work lands that were sacred to Apollo near Delphi, a sacrilege that gave Philip the opportunity to further intervene in Greek affairs.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] While Philip was occupied in Thrace, Alexander was ordered to muster an army for a campaign in southern Greece.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Concerned that other Greek states might intervene, Alexander made it look as though he was preparing to attack Illyria instead.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] During this turmoil, the Illyrians invaded Macedonia, only to be repelled by Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip and his army joined his son in 338 BC, and they marched south through Thermopylae, taking it after stubborn resistance from its Theban garrison.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] They went on to occupy the city of Elatea, only a few days' march from both Athens and Thebes.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The Athenians, led by Demosthenes, voted to seek alliance with Thebes against Macedonia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Both Athens and Philip sent embassies to win Thebes's favour, but Athens won the contest.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip marched on Amphissa (ostensibly acting on the request of the Amphictyonic League), capturing the mercenaries sent there by Demosthenes and accepting the city's surrender.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip then returned to Elatea, sending a final offer of peace to Athens and Thebes, who both rejected it.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] As Philip marched south, his opponents blocked him near Chaeronea, Boeotia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] During the ensuing Battle of Chaeronea, Philip commanded the right wing and Alexander the left, accompanied by a group of Philip's trusted generals.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the ancient sources, the two sides fought bitterly for some time.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip deliberately commanded his troops to retreat, counting on the untested Athenian hoplites to follow, thus breaking their line.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was the first to break the Theban lines, followed by Philip's generals.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Having damaged the enemy's cohesion, Philip ordered his troops to press forward and quickly routed them.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] With the Athenians lost, the Thebans were surrounded.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Left to fight alone, they were defeated.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Following their victory at Chaeronea, Philip and Alexander marched unopposed into the Peloponnese, devastating much of Laconia and ejecting the Spartans from various parts of it.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] At Corinth, Philip established a "Hellenic Alliance" (modelled on the old anti-Persian alliance of the Greco-Persian Wars), which included most Greek city-states except Sparta.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip was then named *Hegemon* (often translated as "Supreme Commander") of this league (known by modern scholars as the League of Corinth), and announced his plans to attack the Persian Empire.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] When Philip returned to Pella, he fell in love with and married Cleopatra Eurydice in 338 BC, the niece of his general Attalus.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The marriage made Alexander's position as heir less secure, since any son of Cleopatra Eurydice would be a fully Macedonian heir, while Alexander was only half-Macedonian.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] During the wedding banquet, a drunken Attalus publicly prayed to the gods that the union would produce a legitimate heir.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] — Plutarch, describing the feud at Philip's wedding.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In 337 BC, Alexander fled Macedon with his mother, dropping her off with her brother, King Alexander I of Epirus in Dodona, capital of the Molossians.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He continued to Illyria where he sought refuge with one or more Illyrian kings, perhaps with Glaucias, and was treated as a guest, despite having defeated them in battle a few years before.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] However, it appears Philip never intended to disown his politically and militarily trained son.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Accordingly, Alexander returned to Macedon after six months due to the efforts of a family friend, Demaratus, who mediated between the two parties.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In the following year, the Persian satrap (governor) of Caria, Pixodarus, offered his eldest daughter to Alexander's half-brother, Philip Arrhidaeus.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Olympias and several of Alexander's friends suggested this showed Philip intended to make Arrhidaeus his heir.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander reacted by sending an actor, Thessalus of Corinth, to tell Pixodarus that he should not offer his daughter's hand to an illegitimate son, but instead to Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] When Philip heard of this, he stopped the negotiations and scolded Alexander for wishing to marry the daughter of a Carian, explaining that he wanted a better bride for him.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip exiled four of Alexander's friends, Harpalus, Nearchus, Ptolemy and Erigyius, and had the Corinthians bring Thessalus to him in chains.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] As Pausanias tried to escape, he tripped over a vine and was killed by his pursuers, including two of Alexander's companions, Perdiccas and Leonnatus.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was proclaimed king on the spot by the nobles and army at the age of 20.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander began his reign by eliminating potential rivals to the throne.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He had his cousin, the former Amyntas IV, executed and two Macedonian princes from the region of Lyncestis killed for having been involved in his father's assassination, but spared a third, Alexander Lyncestes.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Olympias had Cleopatra Eurydice, and Europa, her daughter by Philip, burned alive, though this infuriated Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander also ordered the murder of Cleopatra's uncle Attalus, who was in command of the advance guard of the army in Asia Minor.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Attalus was at that time corresponding with Demosthenes regarding the possibility of defecting to Athens, and had severely insulted Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] After his niece's murder, Alexander may have considered him too dangerous to be left alive.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander spared Arrhidaeus, who was by all accounts mentally disabled, possibly as a result of poisoning by Olympias.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] News of Philip's death roused many states into revolt, including Thebes, Athens, Thessaly, and the Thracian tribes north of Macedon.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] When news of the revolts reached Alexander, he responded quickly.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Though advised to use diplomacy, Alexander mustered 3,000 Macedonian cavalry and rode south towards Thessaly.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He found the Thessalian army occupying the pass between Mount Olympus and Mount Ossa, and ordered his men to ride over Mount Ossa.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] When the Thessalians awoke the next day, they found Alexander in their rear and promptly surrendered, adding their cavalry to Alexander's force.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He then continued south towards the Peloponnese.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander stopped at Thermopylae where he was recognized as the leader of the Amphictyonic League before heading south to Corinth.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Athens sued for peace and Alexander pardoned the rebels.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The famous encounter between Alexander and Diogenes the Cynic occurred during Alexander's stay in Corinth.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander asked Diogenes what he could do for him, the philosopher disdainfully asked Alexander to stand a little to the side, as he was blocking the sunlight.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] This reply apparently delighted Alexander who is reported to have said, "But verily, if I were not Alexander, I would like to be Diogenes." At Corinth, Alexander took the title of *Hegemon* ("leader") and, like Philip, was appointed commander for the coming war against Persia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He also received news of a Thracian uprising.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Before crossing to Asia, Alexander wanted to safeguard his northern borders.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In the spring of 335 BC, he advanced to suppress several revolts.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Starting from Amphipolis, he travelled east into the country of the "Independent Thracians", and at Mount Haemus, the Macedonian army attacked and defeated the Thracian forces manning the heights.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians marched into the country of the Triballi and defeated their army near the Lyginus river (a tributary of the Danube).
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then marched for three days to the Danube, encountering the Getae tribe on the opposite shore.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Crossing the river at night, he surprised them and forced their army to retreat after the first cavalry skirmish.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] News then reached Alexander that the Illyrian chieftain Cleitus and King Glaukias of the Taulantii were in open revolt against his authority.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Marching west into Illyria, Alexander defeated each in turn, forcing the two rulers to flee with their troops.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] With these victories, he secured his northern frontier.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] While Alexander campaigned north, the Thebans and Athenians rebelled once again.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] While the other cities again hesitated, Thebes decided to fight.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The Theban resistance was ineffective and Alexander razed the city and divided its territory between the other Boeotian cities.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The end of Thebes cowed Athens, leaving all of Greece temporarily at peace.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then set out on his Asian campaign, leaving Antipater as regent.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] After securing his Greek base and the Balkans by subjugating his political opponents, and securing his army's rear through the conquest of all the Afro-Asian coastline, where the Persian fleet was based and from which it was supplied, Alexander moved to confront directly the Persians.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In 336 he sent Parmenion, Amyntas, Andromenes, Attalus, and an army of 10,000 men into Anatolia to make preparations for an invasion.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greek cities on the western coast of Anatolia revolted until the news arrived that Philip had been murdered and had been succeeded by his young son Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians were demoralized by Philip's death and were subsequently defeated near Magnesia by the Achaemenids under the command of the mercenary Memnon of Rhodes.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He showed his intent to conquer the entirety of the Persian Empire by throwing a spear into Asian soil and saying he accepted Asia as a gift from the gods.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] This also showed Alexander's eagerness to fight, in contrast to his father's preference for diplomacy.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] After an initial victory against Persian forces at the Battle of the Granicus, Alexander accepted the surrender of the Persian provincial capital and treasury of Sardis; he then proceeded along the Ionian coast, granting autonomy and democracy to the cities.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Miletus, held by Achaemenid forces, required a delicate siege operation, with Persian naval forces nearby.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Further south, at Halicarnassus, in Caria, Alexander successfully waged his first large-scale siege, eventually forcing his opponents, the mercenary captain Memnon of Rhodes and the Persian satrap of Caria, Orontobates, to withdraw by sea.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander left the government of Caria to a member of the Hecatomnid dynasty, Ada, who adopted Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] From Halicarnassus, Alexander proceeded into mountainous Lycia and the Pamphylian plain, asserting control over all coastal cities to deny the Persians naval bases.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] From Pamphylia onwards, the coast held no major ports and Alexander moved inland.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] At Termessos, Alexander humbled and did not storm the Pisidian city.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] At the ancient Phrygian capital of Gordium, Alexander "undid" the hitherto unsolvable Gordian Knot, a feat said to await the future "king of Asia".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the story, Alexander proclaimed that it did not matter how the knot was undone, and hacked it apart with his sword.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In spring 333 BC, Alexander crossed the Taurus into Cilicia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] After a long pause due to an illness, he marched on towards Syria.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Though outmanoeuvered by Darius's significantly larger army, he marched back to Cilicia, where he defeated Darius at Issus.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius fled the battle, causing his army to collapse, and left behind his wife, his two daughters, his mother Sisygambis, and a fabulous treasure.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He offered a peace treaty that included the lands he had lost, and a ransom of 10,000 talents for his family.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander replied that since he was now king of Asia, it was he alone who decided territorial divisions.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander proceeded to take possession of Syria, and most of the coast of the Levant.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In the following year, 332 BC, he was forced to attack Tyre, which he captured after a long and difficult siege.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The men of military age were massacred and the women and children sold into slavery.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander destroyed Tyre, most of the towns on the route to Egypt quickly capitulated.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander was met with resistance at Gaza.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The stronghold was heavily fortified and built on a hill, requiring a siege.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] When "his engineers pointed out to him that because of the height of the mound it would be impossible... this encouraged Alexander all the more to make the attempt".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] After three unsuccessful assaults, the stronghold fell, but not before Alexander had received a serious shoulder wound.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] As in Tyre, men of military age were put to the sword, and the women and children were sold into slavery.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander advanced on Egypt in later 332 BC where he was regarded as a liberator.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] To legitimize taking power and be recognized as the descendant of the long line of pharaohs, Alexander made sacrifices to the gods at Memphis and went to consult the famous oracle of Amun-Ra at the Siwa Oasis in the Libyan desert, at which he was pronounced the son of the deity Amun.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Henceforth, Alexander often referred to Zeus-Ammon as his true father, and after his death, currency depicted him adorned with horns, using the Horns of Ammon as a symbol of his divinity.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greeks interpreted this message – one that the gods addressed to all pharaohs – as a prophecy.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Egypt was only one of a large number of territories taken by Alexander from the Persians.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] After his trip to Siwa, Alexander was crowned in the temple of Ptah at Memphis.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] It appears that the Egyptian people did not find it disturbing that he was a foreigner – nor that he was absent for virtually his entire reign.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander restored the temples neglected by the Persians and dedicated new monuments to the Egyptian gods.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In the temple of Luxor, near Karnak, he built a chapel for the sacred barge.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] During his brief months in Egypt, he reformed the taxation system on the Greek models and organized the military occupation of the country, but in early 331 BC he left for Asia in pursuit of the Persians.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] During his stay in Egypt, he founded Alexandria, which would become the prosperous capital of the Ptolemaic Kingdom after his death.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Control of Egypt passed to Ptolemy I (son of Lagos), the founder of the Ptolemaic Dynasty (305–30 BC) after the death of Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Leaving Egypt in 331 BC, Alexander marched eastward into Achaemenid Assyria in Upper Mesopotamia (now northern Iraq) and defeated Darius again at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius once more fled the field, and Alexander chased him as far as Arbela.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Gaugamela would be the final and decisive encounter between the two.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius fled over the mountains to Ecbatana (modern Hamadan) while Alexander captured Babylon.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Babylonian astronomical diaries say that "the king of the world, Alexander" sent his scouts with a message to the people of Babylon before entering the city: "I shall not enter your houses".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] From Babylon, Alexander went to Susa, one of the Achaemenid capitals, and captured its treasury.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He sent the bulk of his army to the Persian ceremonial capital of Persepolis via the Persian Royal Road.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander himself took selected troops on the direct route to the city.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He then stormed the pass of the Persian Gates (in the modern Zagros Mountains) which had been blocked by a Persian army under Ariobarzanes and then hurried to Persepolis before its garrison could loot the treasury.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] On entering Persepolis, Alexander allowed his troops to loot the city for several days.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander stayed in Persepolis for five months.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] During his stay, a fire broke out in the eastern palace of Xerxes I and spread to the rest of the city.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Possible causes include a drunken accident or deliberate revenge for the burning of the Acropolis of Athens during the Second Persian War by Xerxes; Plutarch and Diodorus allege that Alexander's companion, the hetaera Thaïs, instigated and started the fire.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Even as he watched the city burn, Alexander immediately began to regret his decision.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch claims that he ordered his men to put out the fires but the flames had already spread to most of the city.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Curtius claims that Alexander did not regret his decision until the next morning.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then chased Darius, first into Media, and then Parthia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The Persian king no longer controlled his own destiny, and was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men fatally stab the Great King and then declared himself Darius's successor as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia to launch a guerrilla campaign against Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander buried Darius's remains next to his Achaemenid predecessors in a regal funeral.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He claimed that, while dying, Darius had named him as his successor to the Achaemenid throne.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is normally considered to have fallen with Darius.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander viewed Bessus as an usurper and set out to defeat him.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] This campaign, initially against Bessus, turned into a grand tour of central Asia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander founded a series of new cities, all called Alexandria, including modern Kandahar in Afghanistan, and Alexandria Eschate ("The Furthest") in modern Tajikistan.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The campaign took Alexander through a number of satrapies in present-day Afghanistan and Central Asia, including Media, Parthia, Aria, Drangiana, Arachosia, Bactria, and Scythia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In 329 BC, Spitamenes, who held an undefined position in the satrapy of Sogdiana, betrayed Bessus to Ptolemy, one of Alexander's trusted companions, and Bessus was executed.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] However, at some point later when Alexander was on the Jaxartes dealing with an incursion by a horse nomad army, Spitamenes raised Sogdiana in revolt.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander personally defeated the Scythians at the Battle of Jaxartes and immediately launched a campaign against Spitamenes, defeating him in the Battle of Gabai.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] After the defeat, Spitamenes was killed by his own men, who then sued for peace.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] During this time, Alexander adopted some elements of Persian dress and customs at his court, notably the custom of *proskynesis*, either a symbolic kissing of the hand, or prostration on the ground, that Persians showed to their social superiors.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] This was one aspect of Alexander's broad strategy aimed at securing the aid and support of the Iranian upper classes.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greeks however regarded the gesture of *proskynesis* as the province of deities and believed that Alexander meant to deify himself by requiring it.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] This cost him the sympathies of many of his countrymen, and he eventually abandoned it.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] During the long rule of the Achaemenids, the elite positions in many segments of the empire including the central government, the army, and the many satrapies were specifically reserved for Iranians and to a major degree, Persian noblemen.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The latter were in many cases additionally connected through marriage alliances with the royal Achaemenid family.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] This created a problem for Alexander as to whether he had to make use of the various segments and people that had given the empire its solidity and unity for a lengthy period of time.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Pierre Briant explains that Alexander realized that it was insufficient to merely exploit the internal contradictions within the imperial system as in Asia Minor, Babylonia or Egypt; he also had to (re)create a central government with or without the support of the Iranians.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] As early as 334 BC he demonstrated awareness of this, when he challenged incumbent King Darius III "by appropriating the main elements of the Achaemenid monarchy's ideology, particularly the theme of the king who protects the lands and the peasants".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander wrote a letter in 332 BC to Darius III, wherein he argued that he was worthier than Darius "to succeed to the Achaemenid throne".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander's eventual decision to burn the Achaemenid palace at Persepolis in conjunction with the major rejection and opposition of the "entire Persian people" made it impracticable for him to pose himself as Darius' legitimate successor.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Against Bessus (Artaxerxes V) however, Briant adds, Alexander reasserted "his claim to legitimacy as the avenger of Darius III".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] A plot against his life was revealed, and one of his officers, Philotas, was executed for failing to alert Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The death of the son necessitated the death of the father, and thus Parmenion, who had been charged with guarding the treasury at Ecbatana, was assassinated at Alexander's command, to prevent attempts at vengeance.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Later, in the Central Asian campaign, a second plot against his life was revealed.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] This one was instigated by his own royal pages.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] His official historian, Callisthenes of Olynthus, was implicated in the plot, and in the *Anabasis of Alexander*, Arrian states that Callisthenes and the pages were then tortured on the rack as punishment, and likely died soon after.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] It remains unclear if Callisthenes was actually involved in the plot, for prior to his accusation he had fallen out of favour by leading the opposition to the attempt to introduce proskynesis.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander set out for Asia, he left his general Antipater, an experienced military and political leader, and part of Philip II's "Old Guard", in charge of Macedon.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's sacking of Thebes ensured that Greece remained quiet during his absence.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The one exception was a call to arms by Spartan king Agis III in 331 BC, whom Antipater defeated and killed in the battle of Megalopolis.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Antipater referred the Spartans' punishment to the League of Corinth, which then deferred to Alexander, who chose to pardon them.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] There was also considerable friction between Antipater and Olympias, and each complained to Alexander about the other.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In general, Greece enjoyed a period of peace and prosperity during Alexander's campaign in Asia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander sent back vast sums from his conquest, which stimulated the economy and increased trade across his empire.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander's constant demands for troops and the migration of Macedonians throughout his empire depleted Macedon's strength, greatly weakening it in the years after Alexander, and ultimately led to its subjugation by Rome after the Third Macedonian War (171–168 BC).
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The conquest by Philip II of Pangaeum, and then of the island of Thasos between 356 and 342 BC brought rich gold and silver mines under Macedonian control.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander appears to have introduced a new coinage in Cilicia in Tarsus, after the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, which went on to become the main coinage of the empire.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander minted gold staters, silver tetradrachms and drachims, and various fractional bronze coins.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The types of these coins remained constant in his empire.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The gold series had the head of Athena on the obverse and a winged Nike (Victory) on the reverse.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The silver coinage had a beardless head of Heracles wearing a lionskin headdress on the obverse and Zeus aetophoros ('eagle bearer') enthroned with a scepter in his left hand, on the reverse.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] There are both Greek and non-Greek aspects to this design.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Heracles and Zeus were important deities for the Macedonians, with Heracles considered to be the ancestor of the Temenid dynasty and Zeus the patron of the main Macedonian sanctuary, Dium.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The lion was also the symbolic animal of the Anatolian god Sandas, worshipped at Tarsus.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The reverse design of Alexander's tetradrachms is closely modelled on the depiction of the god Baaltars (Baal of Tarsus), on the silver staters minted at Tarsus by the Persian satrap Mazaeus before Alexander's conquest.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander did not attempt to impose uniform imperial coinage throughout his new conquests.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Persian coins continued to circulate in all the satrapies of the empire.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] After the death of Spitamenes and his marriage to Roxana (Raoxshna in Old Iranian) to cement relations with his new satrapies, Alexander turned to the Indian subcontinent.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He invited the chieftains of the former satrapy of Gandhara (in the present-day Peshawar Valley), to come to him and submit to his authority.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In the winter of 327/326 BC, Alexander personally led Cophen campaign against the Aspasioi of the Kunar Valley, the Guraeans of the Panjkora Valley, and the Assakenoi of the Swat Valley.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] A fierce contest ensued with the Aspasioi in which Alexander was wounded in the shoulder by a dart, but eventually the Aspasioi lost.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then faced the Assakenoi who fought against him from the strongholds of Massaga, Ora, and Aornos.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The fort of Massaga was reduced after days of bloody fighting in which Alexander was seriously wounded in the ankle.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] According to Curtius, "Not only did Alexander slaughter the entire population of Massaga, but also did he reduce its buildings to rubble." A similar massacre followed at Ora.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In the aftermath of Massaga and Ora, numerous Assakenians fled to the fortress of Aornos.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander followed close behind and captured the strategic hill-fort after four bloody days.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] After the death of Assakenoi leader, his mother queen Cleophis submitted to Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] After Aornos, Alexander crossed the Indus.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Omphis hastened to relieve Alexander of his apprehension and met him with valuable presents, placing himself and all his forces at his disposal.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander not only returned Omphis his title and the gifts but he also presented him with a wardrobe of "Persian robes, gold and silver ornaments, 30 horses and 1,000 talents in gold".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] On the subsequent advance of the Macedonian king, Omphis accompanied him with a force of 5,000 men and took part in the Battle of the Hydaspes against the King Porus, who ruled territory lying between the Hydaspes and the Acesines (Chenab) in the Punjab, in 326 BC.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander won an epic battle against Porus.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Omphis was sent by Alexander in pursuit of Porus, to whom he was charged to offer favourable terms, but narrowly escaped losing his life at the hands of his old enemy.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Subsequently, the two rivals were reconciled by the personal mediation of Alexander; Omphis contributed zealously to the equipment of the fleet on the Hydaspes and was entrusted by Alexander with the government of the whole territory between that river and the Indus.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was also impressed by Porus's bravery and made him an ally.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] He appointed Porus as satrap, and added to Porus's territory land that he did not previously own, towards the south-east, up to the Hyphasis (Beas).
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Choosing local rulers helped him control these lands that were distant from Greece.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] A considerable accession of power was granted him after the death of Philip, son of Machatas, and he was allowed to retain his authority at the death of Alexander himself (323 BC), as well as in the subsequent partition of the provinces at Triparadisus, 321 BC.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander founded two cities on opposite sides of the Hydaspes river, naming one Bucephala, in honour of his horse, who died around this time.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The other was Nicaea (Victory), believed to be located at the site of modern-day Mong.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Philostratus the Elder in the *Life of Apollonius of Tyana* writes that in the army of Porus, there was an elephant who fought bravely against Alexander's army, and Alexander dedicated it to the Helios (Sun) and named it Ajax because he thought that such a great animal deserved a great name.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The elephant had gold rings around its tusks and an inscription was on them written in Greek: "Alexander the son of Zeus dedicates Ajax to the Helios" (ΑΛΕΞΑΝΔΡΟΣ Ο ΔΙΟΣ ΤΟΝ ΑΙΑΝΤΑ ΤΩΙ ΗΛΙΩΙ).
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] East of Porus's kingdom, near the Ganges River, was the Nanda Empire of Magadha, and further east, the Gangaridai Empire of Bengal region.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Fearing the prospect of facing other large armies and exhausted by years of campaigning, Alexander's army mutinied at the Hyphasis River (Beas), refusing to march farther east.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] This river thus marks the easternmost extent of Alexander's conquests.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander tried to persuade his soldiers to march farther, but his general Coenus pleaded with him to change his opinion and return; the men, he said, "longed to again see their parents, their wives and children, their homeland".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander eventually agreed and turned south, marching along the Indus.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Along the way his army conquered the territory inhabited by the Mallians in the Mallian campaign; while besieging the Mallian citadel, Alexander suffered a near-fatal injury when an arrow penetrated his armor and entered his lung.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander sent much of his army to Carmania (modern southern Iran) with general Craterus, and commissioned a fleet to explore the Persian Gulf shore under his admiral Nearchus, while he led the rest back to Persia through the more difficult southern route along the Gedrosian Desert and Makran.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander reached Susa in 324 BC, but not before losing many men to the harsh desert.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Discovering that many of his satraps and military governors had misbehaved in his absence, Alexander executed several of them as examples on his way to Susa.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] As a gesture of thanks, he paid off the debts of his soldiers, and announced he would send over-aged and disabled veterans back to Macedon, led by Craterus.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] His troops misunderstood his intention and mutinied at the town of Opis.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] They refused to be sent away and criticized his adoption of Persian customs and dress and the introduction of Persian officers and soldiers into Macedonian units.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] After three days, unable to persuade his men to back down, Alexander gave Persians command posts in the army and conferred Macedonian military titles upon Persian units.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians quickly begged forgiveness, which Alexander accepted, and held a great banquet with several thousand of his men.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] In an attempt to craft a lasting harmony between his Macedonian and Persian subjects, Alexander held a mass marriage of his senior officers to Persian and other noblewomen at Susa, but few of those marriages seem to have lasted much beyond a year.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Meanwhile, upon his return to Persia, Alexander learned that guards of the tomb of Cyrus the Great in Pasargadae had desecrated it, and swiftly executed them.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander admired Cyrus the Great, from an early age reading Xenophon's *Cyropaedia*, which described Cyrus's heroism in battle and governance as a king and legislator.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] During his visit to Pasargadae, Alexander ordered his architect Aristobulus to decorate the interior of the sepulchral chamber of Cyrus's tomb.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Afterwards, Alexander travelled to Ecbatana to retrieve the bulk of the Persian treasure.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] There, his closest friend, Hephaestion, died of illness or poisoning.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Hephaestion's death devastated Alexander and he ordered the preparation of an expensive funeral pyre in Babylon along with a decree for public mourning.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p01] Back in Babylon, Alexander planned a series of new campaigns, beginning with an invasion of Arabia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] On either 10 or 11 June 323 BC, Alexander died in the palace of Nebuchadnezzar II, in Babylon, at age 32.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] There are two different versions of Alexander's death, differing slightly in details.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Plutarch's account is that roughly 14 days before his death, Alexander entertained admiral Nearchus and spent the night and next day drinking with Medius of Larissa.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander developed a fever, which worsened until he was unable to speak.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The common soldiers, anxious about his health, were granted the right to file past him as he silently waved at them.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In the second account, Diodorus recounts that Alexander was struck with pain after downing a large bowl of unmixed wine in honour of Heracles followed by 11 days of weakness; he did not develop a fever, instead dying after some agony.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Arrian also mentioned this as an alternative, but Plutarch specifically denied this claim.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Given the propensity of the Macedonian aristocracy to assassination and Alexander's relatively young age, foul play featured in multiple accounts of his death.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus, Plutarch, Arrian and Justin all mentioned the theory that Alexander was poisoned.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Justin stated that Alexander was the victim of a poisoning conspiracy, Plutarch dismissed it as a fabrication, while both Diodorus and Arrian noted that they mentioned it only for the sake of completeness.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The accounts were nevertheless fairly consistent in designating Antipater, recently removed as Macedonian viceroy, replaced by Craterus, as the head of the alleged plot.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Perhaps taking his summons to Babylon as a death sentence and having seen the fate of Parmenion and Philotas, Antipater purportedly arranged for Alexander to be poisoned by his son Iollas, who was Alexander's wine-pourer.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] There was even a suggestion that Aristotle may have participated.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The strongest argument against the poison theory is the fact that twelve days passed between the start of his illness and his death; such long-acting poisons were probably not available.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in a 2003 BBC documentary investigating the death of Alexander, Leo Schep from the New Zealand National Poisons Centre proposed that the plant white hellebore (*Veratrum album*), which was known in antiquity, may have been used to poison Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In a 2014 manuscript in the journal *Clinical Toxicology*, Schep suggested Alexander's wine was spiked with *Veratrum album*, and that this would produce poisoning symptoms that match the course of events described in the *Alexander Romance*.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] *Veratrum album* poisoning can have a prolonged course and it was suggested that if Alexander was poisoned, *Veratrum album* offers the most plausible cause.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Another poisoning explanation put forward in 2010 proposed that the circumstances of his death were compatible with poisoning by water of the river Styx (modern-day Mavroneri in Arcadia, Greece) that contained calicheamicin, a dangerous compound produced by bacteria.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Several natural causes (diseases) have been suggested, including malaria and typhoid fever.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] A 1998 article in the *New England Journal of Medicine* attributed his death to typhoid fever complicated by bowel perforation and ascending paralysis.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] A 2004 analysis suggested pyogenic (infectious) spondylitis or meningitis.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Other illnesses fit the symptoms, including acute pancreatitis, West Nile virus, and Guillain-Barré syndrome.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Natural-cause theories also tend to emphasize that Alexander's health may have been in general decline after years of heavy drinking and severe wounds.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The anguish that Alexander felt after Hephaestion's death may also have contributed to his declining health.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's body was laid in a gold anthropoid sarcophagus that was filled with honey, which was in turn placed in a gold casket.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Aelian, a seer called Aristander foretold that the land where Alexander was laid to rest "would be happy and unvanquishable forever".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Perhaps more likely, the successors may have seen possession of the body as a symbol of legitimacy, since burying the prior king was a royal prerogative.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] While Alexander's funeral cortege was on its way to Macedon, Ptolemy seized it and took it temporarily to Memphis.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] His successor, Ptolemy II Philadelphus, transferred the sarcophagus to Alexandria, where it remained until at least late antiquity.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Ptolemy IX Lathyros, one of Ptolemy's final successors, replaced Alexander's sarcophagus with a glass one so he could convert the original to coinage.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The 2014 discovery of an enormous tomb in northern Greece, at Amphipolis, dating from the time of Alexander the Great has given rise to speculation that its original intent was to be the burial place of Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] This would fit with the intended destination of Alexander's funeral cortege.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the memorial was found to be dedicated to the dearest friend of Alexander the Great, Hephaestion.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Pompey, Julius Caesar and Augustus all visited the tomb in Alexandria where Augustus, allegedly, accidentally knocked the nose of Alexander's mummified body off.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Caligula was said to have taken Alexander's breastplate from the tomb for his own use.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Around AD 200, Emperor Septimius Severus closed Alexander's tomb to the public.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] His son and successor, Caracalla, a great admirer, visited the tomb during his own reign.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] After this, details on the fate of the tomb are hazy.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The so-called "Alexander Sarcophagus", discovered near Sidon and now in the Istanbul Archaeology Museum, is so named not because it was thought to have contained Alexander's remains, but because its bas-reliefs depict Alexander and his companions fighting the Persians and hunting.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] It was originally thought to have been the sarcophagus of Abdalonymus (died 311 BC), the king of Sidon appointed by Alexander immediately following the Battle of Issus in 332.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in 1969, it was suggested by Karl Schefold that it may date from earlier than Abdalonymus's death.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Demades likened the Macedonian army, after the death of Alexander, to the blinded Cyclops due to the many random and disorderly movements that it made.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In addition, Leosthenes also likened the anarchy between the generals, after Alexander's death, to the blinded Cyclops "who after he had lost his eye went feeling and groping about with his hands before him, not knowing where to lay them".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's death was so sudden that when reports of his death reached Greece, they were not immediately believed.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander had no obvious or legitimate heir, his son Alexander IV by Roxane being born after Alexander's death.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus, Alexander's companions asked him on his deathbed to whom he bequeathed his kingdom; his laconic reply was "tôi kratistôi"—"to the strongest".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Another theory is that his successors wilfully or erroneously misheard "tôi Kraterôi"—"to Craterus", the general leading his Macedonian troops home and newly entrusted with the regency of Macedonia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Arrian and Plutarch claimed that Alexander was speechless by this time, implying that this was an apocryphal story.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus, Curtius and Justin offered the more plausible story that Alexander passed his signet ring to Perdiccas, a bodyguard and leader of the companion cavalry, in front of witnesses, thereby nominating him.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Perdiccas initially did not claim power, instead suggesting that Roxane's baby would be king, if male, with himself, Craterus, Leonnatus, and Antipater as guardians.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the infantry, under the command of Meleager, rejected this arrangement since they had been excluded from the discussion.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Instead, they supported Alexander's half-brother Philip Arrhidaeus.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Eventually, the two sides reconciled, and after the birth of Alexander IV, he and Philip III were appointed joint kings, albeit in name only.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Dissension and rivalry soon affected the Macedonians.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The satrapies handed out by Perdiccas at the Partition of Babylon became power bases each general used to bid for power.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] After the assassination of Perdiccas in 321 BC, Macedonian unity collapsed, and 40 years of war between "The Successors" (*Diadochi*) ensued before the Hellenistic world settled into three stable power blocs: Ptolemaic Egypt, Seleucid Syria and Persia, and Antigonid Macedonia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In the process, both Alexander IV and Philip III were murdered.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus stated that Alexander had given detailed written instructions to Craterus some time before his death, which are known as Alexander's "last plans".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Craterus started to carry out Alexander's commands, but the successors chose not to further implement them, on the grounds they were impractical and extravagant.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Furthermore, Perdiccas had read the notebooks containing Alexander's last plans to the Macedonian troops in Babylon, who voted not to carry them out.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus, Alexander's last plans called for military expansion into the southern and western Mediterranean, monumental constructions, and the intermixing of Eastern and Western populations.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The enormous scale of these plans has led many scholars to doubt their historicity.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Ernst Badian argued that they were exaggerated by Perdiccas in order to ensure that the Macedonian troops voted not to carry them out.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Other scholars have proposed that they were invented by later authors within the tradition of the Alexander Romance.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander perhaps earned the epithet "the Great" due to his unparalleled success as a military commander; he never lost a battle, despite typically being outnumbered.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] This was due to use of terrain, phalanx and cavalry tactics, bold strategy, and the fierce loyalty of his troops.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The Macedonian phalanx, armed with the sarissa, a spear 6 metres (20 ft) long, had been developed and perfected by Philip II through rigorous training, and Alexander used its speed and manoeuvrability to great effect against larger but more disparate Persian forces.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also recognized the potential for disunity among his diverse army, which employed various languages and weapons.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] He overcame this by being personally involved in battle, in the manner of a Macedonian king.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In his first battle in Asia, at Granicus, Alexander used only a small part of his forces, perhaps 13,000 infantry with 5,000 cavalry, against a much larger Persian force of 40,000.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander placed the phalanx at the center and cavalry and archers on the wings, so that his line matched the length of the Persian cavalry line, about 3 km (1.86 mi).
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] By contrast, the Persian infantry was stationed behind its cavalry.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] This ensured that Alexander would not be outflanked, while his phalanx, armed with long pikes, had a considerable advantage over the Persians' scimitars and javelins.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Macedonian losses were negligible compared to those of the Persians.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] At Issus in 333 BC, his first confrontation with Darius, he used the same deployment, and again the central phalanx pushed through.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander personally led the charge in the center, routing the opposing army.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] At the decisive encounter with Darius at Gaugamela, Darius equipped his chariots with scythes on the wheels to break up the phalanx and equipped his cavalry with pikes.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander arranged a double phalanx, with the center advancing at an angle, parting when the chariots bore down and then reforming.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The advance was successful and broke Darius's center, causing the latter to flee once again.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] When faced with opponents who used unfamiliar fighting techniques, such as in Central Asia and India, Alexander adapted his forces to his opponents' style.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Thus, in Bactria and Sogdiana, Alexander successfully used his javelin throwers and archers to prevent outflanking movements, while massing his cavalry at the center.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In India, confronted by Porus's elephant corps, the Macedonians opened their ranks to envelop the elephants and used their sarissas to strike upwards and dislodge the elephants' handlers.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Historical sources frequently give conflicting accounts of Alexander's appearance, and the earliest sources are the most scant in their detail; for example, Arrian describes him simply as "very handsome".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] During his lifetime, Alexander carefully curated his image by commissioning works from famous and great artists of the time.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] This included commissioning sculptures by Lysippos, paintings by Apelles and gem engravings by Pyrgoteles.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Ancient authors recorded that Alexander was so pleased with portraits of himself created by Lysippos that he forbade other sculptors from crafting his image; scholars today, however, find the claim dubious.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Nevertheless, though idealised, Lysippos's sculpture was thought to be the most faithful plastic representation.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] 3rd century BC bust of Alexander from Alexandria, Egypt.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Both Curtius and Diodorus report a story that when Darius III's mother, Sisygambis, first met Alexander and Hephaestion, she assumed that the latter was Alexander because he was the taller and more physically impressive of the two.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Historians have understood the detail of the pleasant fragrance attributed to Alexander as stemming from a belief in ancient Greece that pleasant scents are characteristic of gods and heroes.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The Alexander Mosaic and contemporary coins portray Alexander with "a straight nose, a slightly protruding jaw, full lips and eyes deep set beneath a strongly pronounced forehead".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] He is also described as having a slight upward tilt of his head to the left.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] 235 AD), in his *Varia Historia* (12.14), describes Alexander's hair color as "ξανθὴν" (*xanthen*), which at the time, could mean blond, brown, tawny (light brown) or auburn.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] It is sometimes claimed that Alexander had one blue and one brown eye, referring to the *Alexander Romance*, which is however a fictional account that also claims Alexander "had sharp teeth like fangs" and "did not look like Philip or Olympias".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Reconstruction, based on remaining traces of paint of the original polychromy on the Alexander Sarcophagus from Sidon, indicates that he was depicted with brown eyes and chestnut brown hair.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The Acropolis Museum suggests that trace amounts of red paint on a head statue of Alexander found in 1886 were most likely a base coat for golden hues to be painted over for his hair.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The Pella mosaic of a lion hunt (late 4th century BC) depicts him as having blond hair, with empty spots where their eye stones (which would've been used with semi-precious gems) having been plucked out.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Both of Alexander's parents encouraged his ambitions.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] His father Philip was probably Alexander's most immediate and influential role model, as the young Alexander watched him campaign practically every year, winning victory after victory while ignoring severe wounds.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's relationship with his father "forged" the competitive side of his personality; he had a need to outdo his father, illustrated by his reckless behavior in battle.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] While Alexander worried that his father would leave him "no great or brilliant achievement to be displayed to the world", he also downplayed his father's achievements to his companions.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's mother Olympias similarly had huge ambitions, and encouraged her son to believe it was his destiny to conquer the Persian Empire.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] She instilled a sense of destiny in him, and Plutarch tells how his ambition "kept his spirit serious and lofty in advance of his years".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Plutarch, Alexander also had a violent temper and rash, impulsive nature, which could influence his decision making.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Although Alexander was stubborn and did not respond well to orders from his father, he was open to reasoned debate.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] He had a calmer side—perceptive, logical, and calculating.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] He had a great desire for knowledge, a love for philosophy, and was an avid reader.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] This was no doubt in part due to Aristotle's tutelage; Alexander was intelligent and quick to learn.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] His intelligent and rational side was amply demonstrated by his ability and success as a general.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] He had great self-restraint in "pleasures of the body", in contrast with his lack of self-control with alcohol.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander was erudite and patronized both arts and sciences.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] However, he had little interest in sports or the Olympic Games (unlike his father), seeking only the Homeric ideals of honour (*timê*) and glory (*kudos*).
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] He had great charisma and force of personality, characteristics which made him a great leader.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] His unique abilities were further demonstrated by the inability of any of his generals to unite Macedonia and retain the Empire after his death—only Alexander had the ability to do so.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] During his final years, and especially after the death of Hephaestion, Alexander began to exhibit signs of megalomania and paranoia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] His extraordinary achievements, coupled with his own ineffable sense of destiny and the flattery of his companions, may have combined to produce this effect.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] His delusions of grandeur are readily visible in his will and in his desire to conquer the world, in as much as he is by various sources described as having *boundless ambition*, an epithet, the meaning of which has descended into a historical cliché.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] He appears to have believed himself a deity, or at least sought to deify himself.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Olympias always insisted to him that he was the son of Zeus, an idea apparently confirmed to him by the oracle of Amun at Siwa.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] He began to identify himself as the son of Zeus-Ammon.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] This behaviour cost him the sympathies of many of his countrymen.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also was a pragmatic ruler who understood the difficulties of ruling culturally disparate peoples, many of whom lived in societies where the king was treated as divine.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Thus, rather than megalomania, his behaviour may have been a practical attempt at strengthening his rule and keeping his empire together.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander married three times: Roxana, daughter of the Sogdian nobleman Oxyartes of Bactria, out of love; the Persian princesses Stateira and Parysatis, the former a daughter of Darius III and the latter a daughter of Artaxerxes III, for political reasons.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander apparently had two children by Roxana: a son, who was born in India and died in infancy in November 326 BC, and Alexander IV of Macedon, born after his father's death.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Additionally Heracles of Macedon was claimed to be his illegitimate son born of mistress, Barsine.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also had a close relationship with his friend, general, and bodyguard Hephaestion, the son of a Macedonian noble.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Hephaestion's death devastated Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] This event may have contributed to Alexander's failing health and detached mental state during his final months.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's sexuality has been the subject of speculation and controversy in modern times.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The Roman era writer Athenaeus says, based on the scholar Dicaearchus, who was Alexander's contemporary, that the king "was quite excessively keen on boys", and that Alexander kissed the eunuch Bagoas in public.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] This episode is also told by Plutarch, probably based on the same source.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Historian William Woodthorpe Tarn rejected the stories of Bagoas as fabricated in ancient times to defame Alexander, mainly referring to the Rufus's fairly fictionalized biography of Alexander that criticized the Macedonian's "degeneration" in embracing foreign Persian customs.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in 1958 Badian countered Tarn's arguments, though his concern was the issue of the reliability of sources for Alexander rather than the figure of the eunuch himself.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] None of Alexander's contemporaries, however, are known to have explicitly described Alexander's relationship with Hephaestion as sexual, though the pair was often compared to Achilles and Patroclus, who are often interpreted as a couple.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Some modern historians (e.g., Robin Lane Fox) believe not only that Alexander's youthful relationship with Hephaestion was sexual, but also that their sexual contacts may have continued into adulthood, which went against the social norms of at least some Greek cities, such as Athens.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] However, some modern researchers have tentatively proposed that Macedonia (or at least the Macedonian court) may have been more tolerant of homosexuality between adults.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Peter Green argues that there is little evidence in ancient sources that Alexander had much sexual interest in women; he did not produce an heir until the very end of his life.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] However, Ogden calculates that Alexander, who impregnated his partners three times in eight years, had fathered more children than his father at the same age.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Two of these pregnancies—Stateira's and Barsine's—are of dubious legitimacy.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus Siculus, Alexander accumulated a harem in the style of Persian kings, but he used it rather sparingly, "not wishing to offend the Macedonians", showing great self-control in "pleasures of the body".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Nevertheless, Plutarch described how Alexander was infatuated by Roxana while complimenting him on not forcing himself on her.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Green suggested that, in the context of the period, Alexander formed quite strong friendships with women, including Ada of Caria, who adopted him, and even Darius's mother Sisygambis, who supposedly died from grief upon hearing of Alexander's death.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's legacy extended beyond his military conquests, and his reign marked a turning point in European and Asian history.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] His campaigns greatly increased contacts and trade between East and West, and vast areas to the east were significantly exposed to Greek civilization and influence.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Some of the cities he founded became major cultural centers, many surviving into the 21st century.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] His chroniclers recorded valuable information about the areas through which he marched, while the Greeks themselves got a sense of belonging to a world beyond the Mediterranean.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's most immediate legacy was the introduction of Macedonian rule to huge new swathes of Asia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] At the time of his death, Alexander's empire covered some 5,200,000 km2 (2,000,000 sq mi), and was the largest state of its time.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Many of these areas remained in Macedonian hands or under Greek influence for the next 200–300 years.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The successor states that emerged were, at least initially, dominant forces, and these 300 years are often referred to as the Hellenistic period.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The eastern borders of Alexander's empire began to collapse even during his lifetime.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the power vacuum he left in the northwest of the Indian subcontinent directly gave rise to one of the most powerful Indian dynasties in history, the Maurya Empire.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Taking advantage of this power vacuum, Chandragupta Maurya (referred to in Greek sources as "Sandrokottos"), of relatively humble origin, took control of the Punjab, and with that power base proceeded to conquer the Nanda Empire.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Over the course of his conquests, Alexander founded many cities that bore his name, most of them east of the Tigris.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The first, and greatest, was Alexandria in Egypt, which would become one of the leading Mediterranean cities.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The cities' locations reflected trade routes as well as defensive positions.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] At first, the cities must have been inhospitable, little more than defensive garrisons.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Following Alexander's death, many Greeks who had settled there tried to return to Greece.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] However, a century or so after Alexander's death, many of the Alexandrias were thriving, with elaborate public buildings and substantial populations that included both Greek and local peoples.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In 334 BC, Alexander the Great donated funds for the completion of the new temple of Athena Polias in Priene, in modern-day western Turkey.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] An inscription from the temple, now housed in the British Museum, declares: "King Alexander dedicated [this temple] to Athena Polias." This inscription is one of the few independent archaeological discoveries confirming an episode from Alexander's life.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The temple was designed by Pytheos, one of the architects of the Mausoleum at Halicarnassus.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Libanius wrote that Alexander founded the temple of Zeus Bottiaios (Ancient Greek: Βοττιαίου Δῖός), in the place where later the city of Antioch was built.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Suda wrote that Alexander built a big temple to Sarapis.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In 2023, British Museum experts have suggested the possibility that a Greek temple at Girsu in Iraq, was founded by Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] According to the researchers, recent discoveries suggest that "this site honours Zeus and two divine sons.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The term *Hellenization* was coined by the German historian Johann Gustav Droysen to denote the spread of Greek language, culture, and population into the former Persian empire after Alexander's conquest.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] This process can be seen in such great Hellenistic cities as Alexandria, Antioch and Seleucia (south of modern Baghdad).
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander sought to insert Greek elements into Persian culture and to hybridize Greek and Persian culture, homogenizing the populations of Asia and Europe.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Although his successors explicitly rejected such policies, Hellenization occurred throughout the region, accompanied by a distinct and opposite 'Orientalization' of the successor states.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The core of the Hellenistic culture promulgated by the conquests was essentially Athenian.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The close association of men from across Greece in Alexander's army directly led to the emergence of the largely Attic-based "koine", or "common" Greek dialect.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Koine spread throughout the Hellenistic world, becoming the lingua franca of Hellenistic lands, and eventually the ancestor of modern Greek.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Furthermore, town planning, education, local government, and art current in the Hellenistic period were all based on Classical Greek ideals, evolving into distinct new forms commonly grouped as Hellenistic.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Also, the New Testament was written in the Koine Greek language.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Aspects of Hellenistic culture were still evident in the traditions of the Byzantine Empire in the mid-15th century.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Some of the most pronounced effects of Hellenization can be seen in Afghanistan and India, in the region of the relatively late-rising Greco-Bactrian Kingdom (250–125 BC) (in modern Afghanistan, Pakistan, and Tajikistan) and the Indo-Greek Kingdom (180 BC – 10 AD) in modern Afghanistan and India.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] On the Silk Road trade routes, Hellenistic culture hybridized with Iranian and Buddhist cultures.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The resulting syncretism known as Greco-Buddhism influenced the development of Buddhism and created a culture of Greco-Buddhist art.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] These Greco-Buddhist kingdoms sent some of the first Buddhist missionaries to China, Sri Lanka and Hellenistic Asia and Europe (Greco-Buddhist monasticism).
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Some of the first and most influential figurative portrayals of The Buddha appeared at this time, perhaps modelled on Greek statues of Apollo in the Greco-Buddhist style.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] One Greek king, Menander I, probably became Buddhist, and was immortalized in Buddhist literature as 'Milinda'.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The process of Hellenization also spurred trade between the east and west.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] 'Greek astronomical treatise') and Paulisa Siddhanta texts depict the influence of Greek astronomical ideas on Indian astronomy.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Following the conquests of Alexander the Great in the east, Hellenistic influence on Indian art was far-reaching.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In architecture, a few examples of the Ionic order can be found as far as Pakistan with the Jandial temple near Taxila.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Several examples of capitals displaying Ionic influences can be seen as far as Patna, especially with the Pataliputra capital, dated to the 3rd century BC.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The Corinthian order is also heavily represented in the art of Gandhara, especially through Indo-Corinthian capitals.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander and his exploits were admired by many Romans, especially generals, who wanted to associate themselves with his achievements.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Polybius began his *Histories* by reminding Romans of Alexander's achievements, and thereafter Roman leaders saw him as a role model.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Pompey the Great adopted the epithet "Magnus" and even Alexander's anastole-type haircut, and searched the conquered lands of the east for Alexander's 260-year-old cloak, which he then wore as a sign of greatness.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Julius Caesar dedicated a Lysippean equestrian bronze statue, but replaced Alexander's head with his own, while Octavian visited Alexander's tomb in Alexandria and temporarily changed his seal from a sphinx to Alexander's profile.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The emperor Trajan also admired Alexander, as did Nero and Caracalla.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The Macriani, a Roman family that in the person of Macrinus briefly ascended to the imperial throne, kept images of Alexander on their persons, either on jewellery or embroidered into their clothes.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] On the other hand, some Roman writers, particularly Republican figures, used Alexander as a cautionary tale of how autocratic tendencies can be kept in check by the values of the Roman Republic.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander was used by these writers as an example of ruler values such as *amicitia* (friendship) and *clementia* (clemency), but also *iracundia* (anger) and *cupiditas gloriae* (over-desire for glory).
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Emperor Julian in his satire called "The Caesars", describes a contest between the previous Roman emperors, with Alexander the Great called in as an extra contestant, in the presence of the assembled gods.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The Itinerarium Alexandri is a 4th-century Latin description of Alexander the Great's campaigns.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Julius Caesar went to serve his quaestorship in Hispania after his wife's funeral, in the spring or early summer of 69 BC.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] While there, he encountered a statue of Alexander the Great, and realised with dissatisfaction that he was now at an age when Alexander had the world at his feet, while he had achieved comparatively little.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Pompey posed as the "new Alexander" since he was his boyhood hero.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] After Caracalla concluded his campaign against the Alamanni, it became evident that he was inordinately preoccupied with Alexander the Great.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] He began openly mimicking Alexander in his personal style.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In planning his invasion of the Parthian Empire, Caracalla decided to arrange 16,000 of his men in Macedonian-style phalanxes, despite the Roman army having made the phalanx an obsolete tactical formation.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The historian Christopher Matthew mentions that the term *Phalangarii* has two possible meanings, both with military connotations.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] As a consequence, the *Phalangarii* of Legio II Parthica may not have been pikemen, but rather standard battle line troops or possibly *Triarii*.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Caracalla's mania for Alexander went so far that Caracalla visited Alexandria while preparing for his Persian invasion and persecuted philosophers of the Aristotelian school based on a legend that Aristotle had poisoned Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] This was a sign of Caracalla's increasingly erratic behaviour.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] But this mania for Alexander, strange as it was, was overshadowed by subsequent events in Alexandria.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In AD 39, Caligula performed a spectacular stunt by ordering a temporary floating bridge to be built using ships as pontoons, stretching for over two miles from the resort of Baiae to the neighbouring port of Puteoli.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] It was said that the bridge was to rival the Persian king Xerxes' pontoon bridge crossing of the Hellespont.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Caligula, who could not swim, then proceeded to ride his favourite horse Incitatus across, wearing the breastplate of Alexander the Great.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] This act was in defiance of a prediction by Tiberius's soothsayer Thrasyllus of Mendes that Caligula had "no more chance of becoming emperor than of riding a horse across the Bay of Baiae".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The diffusion of Greek culture and language cemented by Alexander's conquests in West Asia and North Africa served as a "precondition" for the later Roman expansion into these territories and entire basis for the Byzantine Empire, according to Errington.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander wrote and received numerous letters, but no originals survive.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] A few official letters addressed to the Greek cities survive in copies inscribed in stone and the content of others is sometimes reported in historical sources.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] These only occasionally quote the letters and it is an open question how reliable such quotations are.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Several fictitious letters, some perhaps based on actual letters, made their way into the *Romance* tradition.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Many of the legends about Alexander derive from his own lifetime, probably encouraged by Alexander himself.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] His court historian Callisthenes portrayed the sea in Cilicia as drawing back from him in proskynesis.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Writing shortly after Alexander's death, Onesicritus invented a tryst between Alexander and Thalestris, queen of the mythical Amazons.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In the first centuries after Alexander's death, probably in Alexandria, a quantity of the legendary material coalesced into a text known as the *Alexander Romance*, later falsely ascribed to Callisthenes and therefore known as *Pseudo-Callisthenes*.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] This text underwent over one hundred recensions, translations, and derivations throughout the Islamic and European worlds in premodern times, containing many dubious stories, and was translated into twenty-five languages, for example Middle Persian, Syriac and Arabic.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander the Great's accomplishments and legacy have been depicted in many cultures.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander has featured in both high and popular culture, beginning from his own era to the present day.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The *Alexander Romance*, in particular, has had a significant impact on portrayals of Alexander in later cultures, from Persian to medieval European, to modern Greek.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander features prominently in modern Greek folklore, more than any other ancient figure.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The colloquial form of his name in modern Greek ("O Megalexandros") is a household name, and he is the only ancient hero to appear in the Karagiozis shadow play.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] One well-known fable among Greek seamen involves a solitary mermaid who would grasp a ship's prow during a storm and ask the captain, "Is King Alexander alive?" The answer should be "He is alive and well and rules the world!" causing the mermaid to vanish and the sea to calm.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Any other answer would cause the mermaid to turn into a raging Gorgon who would drag the ship to the bottom of the sea, all hands aboard.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In pre-Islamic Middle Persian (Zoroastrian) literature, Alexander is referred to by the epithet *gujastak*, meaning "accursed", and is accused of destroying temples and burning the sacred texts of Zoroastrianism.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In Islamic Persia, under the influence of the *Alexander Romance* (in Persian: اسکندرنامه *Iskandarnameh*), a more positive portrayal of Alexander emerges.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Firdausi's *Shahnameh* ("The Book of Kings") includes Alexander in a line of legitimate Persian shahs, a mythical figure who explored the far reaches of the world in search of the Fountain of Youth.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In the *Shahnameh*, Alexander's first journey is to Mecca to pray at the Kaaba.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander was depicted as performing a Hajj (pilgrimage to Mecca) many times in subsequent Islamic art and literature.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Later Persian writers associate him with philosophy, portraying him at a symposium with figures such as Socrates, Plato and Aristotle, in search of immortality.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The figure of Dhu al-Qarnayn (Arabic: ذو القرنين; lit.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] 'The Two-Horned One') is believed by the majority of modern researchers of the Qur'an as well as Islamic commentators to be a reference to Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The figure is also believed by scholars to be based on later legends of Alexander.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In this tradition, he was a heroic figure who built a wall to defend against the nations of Gog and Magog.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] He also travelled the known world in search of the Water of Life and Immortality, eventually becoming a prophet.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The Syriac version of the *Alexander Romance* portrays him as an ideal Christian world conqueror who prayed to "the one true God".
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In Egypt, Alexander was portrayed as the son of Nectanebo II, the last pharaoh before the Persian conquest.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] His defeat of Darius was depicted as Egypt's salvation, "proving" Egypt was still ruled by an Egyptian.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Josephus, Alexander was shown the Book of Daniel when he entered Jerusalem, which described a mighty Greek king who would conquer the Persian Empire.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] This is cited as a reason for sparing Jerusalem.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In Hindi and Urdu, the name "Sikandar", derived from the Persian name for Alexander, denotes a rising young talent, and the Delhi Sultanate ruler Alauddin Khalji stylized himself as "Sikandar-i-Sani" (the Second Alexander the Great).
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] In medieval Europe, Alexander the Great was revered as a member of the Nine Worthies; a group of heroes whose lives were believed to encapsulate all the ideal qualities of chivalry.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] During the first Italian campaign of the French Revolutionary Wars, in a question from Bourrienne, asking whether he gave his preference to Alexander or Caesar, Napoleon said that he places Alexander The Great in the first rank, the main reason being his campaign on Asia.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Apart from a few inscriptions and fragments, texts written by people who actually knew Alexander or who gathered information from men who served with Alexander were all lost.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Contemporaries who wrote accounts of his life included Alexander's campaign historian Callisthenes, Alexander's generals; Ptolemy and Nearchus, Aristobulus, a junior officer on the campaigns, and Onesicritus, Alexander's chief helmsman.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Their works are lost, but later works based on these original sources have survived.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] The earliest of these is Diodorus Siculus (1st century BC), followed by Quintus Curtius Rufus (mid-to-late 1st century AD), Arrian (1st to 2nd century AD), the biographer Plutarch (1st to 2nd century AD), and finally Justin, whose work dated as late as the 4th century.
[src:alexander-the-great/alexander-the-great-p02] Of these, Arrian is generally considered the most reliable, given that he used Ptolemy and Aristobulus as his sources, closely followed by Diodorus.
[src:alexander-the-great/apepi] 'Apepi's only secure attestation is the Turin canon, a king list redacted in the Ramesside period.
[src:alexander-the-great/apepi] 'Apepi is listed on a fragment of the document corresponding to column 10, row 15 (column 9 row 16 as per Alan H.
[src:alexander-the-great/apepi] Gardiner's reconstruction of the Turin canon).
[src:alexander-the-great/apepi] The chronological position of 'Apepi cannot be ascertained beyond doubt due to the fragile and fragmentary state of the canon.
[src:alexander-the-great/apepi] Furthermore, the document preserves only the beginning of 'Apepi's prenomen as "'Ap[...]". which, Ryholt argues, may be restored to "'Apepi".
[src:alexander-the-great/apepi] Ryholt's reconstruction of the name of 'Apepi is significant because five scarab seals inscribed with "King's son Apophis" are known.
[src:alexander-the-great/apepi] On two of these seals the inscription is furthermore enclosed in a cartouche and followed by *di-ˁnḫ* meaning "given life".
[src:alexander-the-great/apepi] These two attributes are normally reserved to kings or designated heirs to the throne and 'Apepi could be the Apophis referred to on the seals.
[src:alexander-the-great/apepi] Tentatively confirming this attribution, Ryholt notes that both scarabs can be dated on stylistic grounds to the 14th Dynasty, between the reigns of Sheshi and Yaqub-Har.
